01:27.454 --> 01:29.650
I'm going to bring
her out here right now.

01:29.722 --> 01:30.848
Dolores.

01:51.077 --> 01:53.239
While the Reverend
Martin Luther King, Jr.

01:53.313 --> 01:55.509
Was leading the charge
in the South,

01:55.582 --> 01:58.381
one California woman
was fighting on the front lines

01:58.451 --> 01:59.850
for workers' rights.

02:02.455 --> 02:05.823
And while her name is rarely
mentioned in the history books,

02:05.892 --> 02:07.257
she may just be

02:07.327 --> 02:11.491
the most vocal activist
you've never heard of.

02:11.564 --> 02:14.226
Come along, brothers.
We are waiting for you!

02:14.300 --> 02:18.362
Dolores Huerta helped
lead a worldwide grape boycott

02:18.438 --> 02:19.667
that forced growers to agree

02:19.739 --> 02:22.640
to some of the country's
first farmworker contracts.

02:25.111 --> 02:26.111
<i>Viva la cause!</i>

02:27.113 --> 02:29.241
<i>Viva la huelgal.</i>

02:29.315 --> 02:32.615
She's the first general
that I followed into war.

02:35.088 --> 02:38.251
The workers are on the rise.

02:38.324 --> 02:40.622
Dolores Huerta,
who is an old friend of mine...

02:42.896 --> 02:45.627
What she is, she's an insult
to the farmworker.

02:45.698 --> 02:48.395
Why are the growers and
the teamsters so against her?

02:48.468 --> 02:49.731
Because they're threatened.

02:52.205 --> 02:54.674
We're never giving up.

02:54.741 --> 02:56.106
Dolores is an icon.

02:56.176 --> 02:58.372
Dolores Huerta has said

02:58.444 --> 02:59.969
Republicans hate Latinos.

03:03.116 --> 03:04.914
She also writes

03:04.984 --> 03:08.284
the alternative to capitalism is
democratic socialism.

03:08.354 --> 03:09.398
She's not afraid

03:09.422 --> 03:10.912
to speak truth to power.

03:14.694 --> 03:15.718
She's a clown.

03:15.795 --> 03:18.389
We thank you
for all you have done

03:18.464 --> 03:19.693
and all you still do

03:19.766 --> 03:21.325
to promote the dignity
and human rights

03:21.401 --> 03:23.096
of America's family.

03:25.572 --> 03:27.597
She's a civil rights hero.

03:27.674 --> 03:30.075
She's been beaten up
and she's gone to jail.

03:30.143 --> 03:31.076
She's a very volatile
individual.

03:31.144 --> 03:32.407
We always like to say

03:32.478 --> 03:34.638
that we didn't cross the border,
the border crossed us.

03:34.681 --> 03:37.013
The FBI knew

03:37.083 --> 03:38.123
how dangerous Dolores was.

03:41.487 --> 03:43.751
Conservatives on
the Texas Board of Education

03:43.823 --> 03:46.758
removed the legendary farmworker
organizer Dolores Huerta

03:46.826 --> 03:49.625
from the state social studies
curriculum.

03:49.696 --> 03:51.240
I got to tell you,
I never heard of this woman.

03:51.264 --> 03:52.129
We've really got

03:52.198 --> 03:53.359
to set the record straight.

03:53.433 --> 03:55.731
I mean, women cannot be written
out of history.

04:06.646 --> 04:08.114
You were a young girl,

04:08.181 --> 04:10.411
growing up in America
in the '40s.

04:10.483 --> 04:12.918
You must have had a dream.

04:15.488 --> 04:17.466
I guess my only dream
was just to be accepted.

04:17.490 --> 04:20.653
I think that's what
a lot of young children feel,

04:20.726 --> 04:24.857
just to be accepted for what you
are and that's not possible.

04:24.931 --> 04:27.059
Tell me when
you were first aware

04:27.133 --> 04:29.329
of having a social conscience.

04:29.402 --> 04:31.734
I think that
I felt it very deeply

04:31.804 --> 04:35.035
as a teenager and it was mostly
because of the police brutality

04:35.108 --> 04:38.043
against Mexicans and blacks,

04:38.111 --> 04:40.773
the kids that I grew up with,

04:40.847 --> 04:43.544
and you find out that
the justice, it's not there.

04:43.616 --> 04:46.551
The equality isn't there.

04:46.619 --> 04:49.350
If you were coming of age
in the 19505

04:49.422 --> 04:52.824
in California
in the San Joaquin Valley,

04:52.892 --> 04:56.226
you were coming of age
in a time of conformity.

04:56.296 --> 04:59.630
Everybody was being fit
into a mold,

04:59.699 --> 05:01.963
and if you were Dolores Huerta,

05:02.035 --> 05:04.367
there was no mold.

05:04.437 --> 05:06.115
My mom, she grew up in the '40s,

05:06.139 --> 05:08.801
you know, like the dances,
the bebop, the big band,

05:08.875 --> 05:09.875
the swing, you know.

05:09.909 --> 05:11.673
She's an American girl,
you know.

05:11.744 --> 05:14.941
Back in those days,
all of the Latina women

05:15.014 --> 05:18.211
got married very young...
15,16,17 years old.

05:18.284 --> 05:21.083
My first husband,
we had a lot in common.

05:21.154 --> 05:22.644
We were both into jazz,

05:22.722 --> 05:25.692
but I don't think that
we were ready for marriage yet.

05:25.758 --> 05:29.160
Then my second husband,
we had kind of a culture clash

05:29.228 --> 05:30.696
because of the way
that I grew up

05:30.763 --> 05:32.197
and the way that he grew up.

05:32.265 --> 05:35.428
My mother was a single parent,
she was a businesswoman,

05:35.501 --> 05:38.198
and like her,
I worked all the time.

05:38.271 --> 05:40.015
You know, my mother-in-law
could never understand why

05:40.039 --> 05:41.973
I didn't just stay home
with the children.

05:42.041 --> 05:46.000
And so, Dolores talks about
her life as a young mother

05:46.079 --> 05:47.843
and as a married woman

05:47.914 --> 05:49.678
and not feeling
that was quite enough,

05:49.749 --> 05:53.481
that she needed to do
more than that.

05:53.553 --> 05:55.612
That's when she met Fred Ross.

05:56.989 --> 05:59.219
When I met Fred
Ross and he talked to me

05:59.292 --> 06:00.760
about how people could
get together

06:00.827 --> 06:02.805
in an organization and really
start changing things,

06:02.829 --> 06:04.593
to me it was just a revelation.

06:04.664 --> 06:07.895
LORI de LEON: Fred Ross
was a community organizer

06:07.967 --> 06:10.493
with the Community Service
Organization

06:10.570 --> 06:12.629
who developed house meetings.

06:12.705 --> 06:14.070
You're on the ground,

06:14.140 --> 06:17.007
identifying individuals
who are willing, you know,

06:17.076 --> 06:19.875
to do the work
to make the communities better.

06:19.946 --> 06:22.813
I still remember
my first house meeting.

06:22.882 --> 06:24.493
Fred showed us pictures
of the improvements

06:24.517 --> 06:26.986
that they had done
in East Los Angeles,

06:27.053 --> 06:29.249
like bringing in
street lights and sidewalks,

06:29.322 --> 06:31.188
bringing in health clinics.

06:31.257 --> 06:32.816
But the one that
really hooked me

06:32.892 --> 06:35.657
was when he showed us
press clippings of police

06:35.728 --> 06:37.787
that they had sent to prison

06:37.864 --> 06:40.595
for beating up
Mexican-American kids.

06:40.666 --> 06:42.478
And I thought, any organization
that can do that,

06:42.502 --> 06:44.766
I want to belong
to that organization.

06:46.472 --> 06:48.907
I think that my mom experienced

06:48.975 --> 06:51.740
enough of that injustice
or discrimination to where

06:51.811 --> 06:54.075
she just could not keep it down.

06:54.147 --> 06:55.581
She could not keep quiet.

06:57.617 --> 06:59.984
In 1959, I became
the political director

07:00.052 --> 07:01.952
for the Community Service
Organization,

07:02.021 --> 07:04.547
and helped draft
a lot of the legislation

07:04.624 --> 07:07.491
that we ultimately got approved
in Sacramento.

07:07.560 --> 07:09.460
I was only 25 at this time,
or 26 years old.

07:09.529 --> 07:11.088
I was very young.

07:11.164 --> 07:13.496
There were
very, very few Latinos-

07:13.566 --> 07:15.056
and I'm talking about men...

07:15.134 --> 07:18.001
In the legislature in California
in the '50s and '60s.

07:18.070 --> 07:19.663
It was all white men,

07:19.739 --> 07:21.639
and here you have someone

07:21.707 --> 07:23.573
like Dolores Huerta,
that was just...

07:23.643 --> 07:25.907
People just didn't do that
in those days.

07:25.978 --> 07:30.279
We had one piece of legislation
to take away the requirement

07:30.349 --> 07:31.783
that you had to be
a U.S. citizen

07:31.851 --> 07:33.580
to get public assistance.

07:33.653 --> 07:36.714
I took parents whose kids
had served in World War II

07:36.789 --> 07:40.316
to this one senator who was key
for us to get that legislation,

07:40.393 --> 07:41.952
sat them in his office

07:42.028 --> 07:45.658
with the pictures of their kids
in uniform.

07:45.731 --> 07:47.324
They couldn't speak English,

07:47.400 --> 07:49.767
Senator Kolbe couldn't speak
Spanish, but I told them,

07:49.836 --> 07:51.634
"Just stay here
until he says yes,

07:51.704 --> 07:53.468
that he'll vote on that bill."

07:53.539 --> 07:55.200
What kind of a lobbyist is she?

07:55.274 --> 07:57.242
Oh, she's a great lobbyist.

07:57.310 --> 07:59.506
She's indefatigable.

07:59.579 --> 08:00.944
She's unorthodox.

08:01.013 --> 08:03.345
You know, Dolores will bring in
hundreds of people

08:03.416 --> 08:05.851
and they'll camp
outside your office.

08:05.918 --> 08:07.716
So when Dolores
is in Sacramento,

08:07.787 --> 08:10.722
everybody knows
she's in Sacramento.

08:10.790 --> 08:13.589
Fred Ross was
always talking about

08:13.659 --> 08:16.094
this great organizer,
Cesar Chavez,

08:16.162 --> 08:18.995
so Fred introduced us.

08:19.065 --> 08:21.227
Cesar was very shy.

08:21.300 --> 08:22.597
I remember one time

08:22.668 --> 08:24.762
that he was sitting down
by himself at a table

08:24.837 --> 08:26.635
and so I rushed over
and sat down

08:26.706 --> 08:28.697
and started trying
to talk to him

08:28.774 --> 08:30.936
and he immediately got up
and walked away.

08:31.010 --> 08:34.775
Fred would always tell
Cesar how he met this woman,

08:34.847 --> 08:37.578
she's dynamite, great organizer.

08:37.650 --> 08:39.118
He was a little bit jealous

08:39.184 --> 08:41.414
when Fred would talk to him
about her.

08:41.486 --> 08:43.011
He was a little bit jealous
about that.

08:43.089 --> 08:45.649
I gave my report
on the legislative work

08:45.725 --> 08:47.693
that we were doing
up in Sacramento.

08:47.760 --> 08:50.161
He and Fred Ross came over
and invited me

08:50.229 --> 08:51.458
to have lunch with them

08:51.531 --> 08:53.465
so I was very thrilled,
because I thought,

08:53.533 --> 08:57.333
"Oh my, Cesar's finally paying
attention to what I'm doing."

08:57.403 --> 09:01.533
They were having a meeting and
they needed a Chicano legislator

09:01.607 --> 09:05.601
to do some things and he was
arguing why it couldn't be done.

09:05.678 --> 09:08.010
And it was when my mother
began telling him

09:08.080 --> 09:10.174
all the reasons why he needed
to get done

09:10.249 --> 09:12.149
that Cesar took a step back
and he goes,

09:12.218 --> 09:15.119
"Now I see what Fred
was talking about."

09:17.356 --> 09:19.051
All this work
that we were doing,

09:19.125 --> 09:21.526
Cesar organizing the farmworkers
in Oxnard,

09:21.594 --> 09:24.029
my organizing farmworkers
in Stockton,

09:24.096 --> 09:27.555
was under the auspices of the
Community Service Organization.

09:27.633 --> 09:29.965
But when it came time then
to make it a union,

09:30.036 --> 09:33.028
the CS0 decided
not to support us.

09:33.105 --> 09:36.735
That's when Cesar called me
to come over to his house

09:36.809 --> 09:39.403
and he said,
"We have to organize a union."

09:39.478 --> 09:42.812
He put it this way, he said,
"Unless you and I do it,

09:42.882 --> 09:44.976
it's never going to happen."

09:45.051 --> 09:46.951
And then he said
in the next breath,

09:47.019 --> 09:50.455
"But we will not see
a national union in our lifetime

09:50.523 --> 09:53.652
"because the growers are
too rich, they're too powerful,

09:53.726 --> 09:56.957
and they're too racist."

10:13.079 --> 10:15.514
One of the really
tragic contradictions

10:15.581 --> 10:18.175
about the United States
of America is that

10:18.250 --> 10:20.014
it has presented itself
before the world

10:20.086 --> 10:24.546
as a beacon of independence
and liberty and human rights.

10:24.624 --> 10:25.955
Of course,

10:26.025 --> 10:31.054
the real stain on this mythology
is slavery

10:31.130 --> 10:35.829
and with it, the potential
for the enslavement of others.

10:35.901 --> 10:37.926
This was a very real threat
for all Mexicans

10:38.004 --> 10:40.234
living in California.

10:40.306 --> 10:42.070
After 1848,

10:42.141 --> 10:43.885
it was a continuing threat
for all of the immigrants

10:43.909 --> 10:48.176
that came from China, Japan,
the Philippines, Vietnam.

10:48.247 --> 10:51.114
Racism has been endemic
to American history.

10:51.183 --> 10:56.212
The feudal wage slavery
of agribusiness

10:56.288 --> 10:58.017
is really just an extension
of the attitude

10:58.090 --> 11:00.491
that had persisted
in the country

11:00.559 --> 11:03.324
and the irony is that none of us
can live without food.

11:03.396 --> 11:06.627
None of us can live without
what's produced in our fields.

11:06.699 --> 11:08.292
This is life,

11:08.367 --> 11:14.568
and yet these are the worst-paid
workers on the planet.

11:14.640 --> 11:17.837
When we came
here to this little, tiny town

11:17.910 --> 11:20.902
in California called Delano,

11:20.980 --> 11:23.915
I started working in the fields
when I was 15 years old

11:23.983 --> 11:26.577
and they were paying
90 cents per hour.

11:26.652 --> 11:29.087
There was no cold drinking water

11:29.155 --> 11:31.852
and the weather gets to be
about 115 degrees.

11:31.924 --> 11:34.052
If you complained
about any of these conditions,

11:34.126 --> 11:36.925
you were told
to get the hell out.

11:36.996 --> 11:38.206
There were plenty
of other people

11:38.230 --> 11:40.164
that could come
and take your place.

11:40.232 --> 11:43.258
And the women
were treated worse than the men.

11:43.335 --> 11:44.666
You had no protection.

11:44.737 --> 11:46.000
There was a lot of mistreatment

11:46.072 --> 11:47.972
and a lot of rape,
there was a lot of...

11:48.040 --> 11:49.838
I mean there's a lot
of that went on.

11:49.909 --> 11:53.436
My grandfather
was living on a vineyard

11:53.512 --> 11:58.712
in a house that was owned
by the people who employed him.

11:58.784 --> 12:01.412
It was sort of this sense
of slavery, right?

12:01.487 --> 12:04.013
You couldn't do anything wrong
against your employer,

12:04.090 --> 12:06.991
because if you did, were they
going to kick out your family?

12:07.059 --> 12:08.493
Where were you going to go?

12:08.561 --> 12:09.756
You don't speak the language.

12:09.829 --> 12:11.991
You're not even a citizen
of the country yet.

12:12.064 --> 12:13.241
They used to say

12:13.265 --> 12:15.029
that they wanted
to hire Mexicans

12:15.101 --> 12:18.162
because we were built
closer to the ground,

12:18.237 --> 12:21.969
and that, in my opinion,
was the worst part:

12:22.041 --> 12:26.911
The humiliation of knowing that
people held you in contempt.

12:33.419 --> 12:38.823
After I had seen the
miserable conditions of farmworkers

12:38.891 --> 12:41.326
and knowing
how to organize people,

12:41.393 --> 12:45.057
having achieved these incredible
successes on legislation,

12:45.131 --> 12:48.897
I just felt that
that's what I needed to do.

12:48.968 --> 12:50.458
It was just such a calling.

12:50.536 --> 12:54.734
I felt it so strongly that
in spite of all of the negatives

12:54.807 --> 12:56.707
that you might think,
"You can't do that.

12:56.776 --> 12:58.210
"You've got seven kids.

12:58.277 --> 12:59.921
You're going through
the middle of a divorce."

12:59.945 --> 13:03.575
Many people thought I was making
a very foolish decision.

13:06.318 --> 13:09.948
LORI de LEON:
My uncles, my aunts,

13:10.022 --> 13:12.889
our family didn't understand
why my mother

13:12.958 --> 13:14.221
would give up everything

13:14.293 --> 13:16.455
to work with farmworkers
who have nothing.

13:16.529 --> 13:20.762
I did pray that if I
was doing the wrong thing,

13:20.833 --> 13:23.803
I wanted a sign that I was doing
the wrong thing.

13:23.869 --> 13:28.067
Making this huge, huge decision
to leave my home in Stockton,

13:28.140 --> 13:31.110
to come to Delano,
not knowing where my next meal

13:31.177 --> 13:32.736
was going to be coming from.

13:32.812 --> 13:36.271
I was worried about how my kids
would be able to take the move

13:36.348 --> 13:38.214
because they left
all their friends behind

13:38.284 --> 13:40.218
and we had
a very comfortable home.

13:40.286 --> 13:43.483
I left a couple of my younger
children behind.

13:43.556 --> 13:48.323
I knew that I was doing
something that I wanted to do.

13:48.394 --> 13:49.418
They had no choice.

13:51.664 --> 13:55.066
The last thing that I did
before I went to Delano,

13:55.134 --> 13:57.899
I went to the
Monterey Jazz Festival.

13:57.970 --> 13:59.460
I always loved jazz music,

13:59.538 --> 14:02.473
and that was one of
the big sacrifices that I made

14:02.541 --> 14:05.033
when I went to Delano
because after that,

14:05.110 --> 14:07.977
I didn't hear any music for...
for years.

14:18.090 --> 14:19.819
LORI de LEON:
It was very, very sad.

14:19.892 --> 14:21.291
We went from a home

14:21.360 --> 14:22.885
where we were surrounded
by family,

14:22.962 --> 14:24.452
to Delano,

14:24.530 --> 14:25.998
first and foremost because

14:26.065 --> 14:28.830
we didn't have our mother
at that point.

14:28.901 --> 14:30.266
She was off and running.

14:30.336 --> 14:33.033
We soon recognized
that my mother

14:33.105 --> 14:34.470
really didn't belong to us.

14:46.385 --> 14:48.786
The reason for the existence
of the union

14:48.854 --> 14:50.720
is to try to get power
for the powerless.

14:50.789 --> 14:52.553
The farmworkers
don't have any power

14:52.625 --> 14:54.669
to solve any of their own
economic and social problems.

14:54.693 --> 14:57.013
You know, they're faced by
not only economic discrimination

14:57.062 --> 14:59.360
and social,
but also racial discrimination.

14:59.431 --> 15:01.525
This is true
of the Mexican farmworkers.

15:01.600 --> 15:03.864
It is of the black farmworker,
the Arabian,

15:03.936 --> 15:05.680
and sometimes even
the poor white farmworker.

15:05.704 --> 15:08.537
Cesar, what
made you pick Dolores,

15:08.607 --> 15:11.338
a woman, to help you form
the United Farm Workers?

15:11.410 --> 15:13.105
We had worked before together,

15:13.178 --> 15:16.637
and she believed as I did

15:16.715 --> 15:18.308
that this job could be done,

15:18.384 --> 15:20.011
the workers could be organized.

15:20.085 --> 15:25.023
She had the faith and the drive
and the enthusiasm.

15:25.090 --> 15:26.489
So those are
some of the reasons.

15:26.558 --> 15:30.552
The... the skills,
a lot of knowledge,

15:30.629 --> 15:34.156
and a lot of just willingness
to sacrifice.

15:38.704 --> 15:41.139
We divided the
San Joaquin Valley.

15:41.206 --> 15:43.800
Cesar took the southern half,
I took the northern half,

15:43.876 --> 15:46.641
and we did house meetings
in all the different counties.

15:46.712 --> 15:49.409
So we had all of these
committees that we organized.

15:49.481 --> 15:52.746
We had a thousand members
and we had benefits.

15:52.818 --> 15:55.150
We had a life insurance plan.

15:55.220 --> 15:57.348
We had an office,
we started a credit union,

15:57.423 --> 15:59.303
the first farmworker
credit union in the history

15:59.358 --> 16:02.726
of the United States of America,
where people could get loans.

16:02.795 --> 16:04.058
We had a cooperative store.

16:04.129 --> 16:06.154
We did services,
we did immigration work,

16:06.231 --> 16:07.665
we did their income taxes.

16:07.733 --> 16:11.033
We had a five-year plan
to have a national strike

16:11.103 --> 16:12.662
in the Central Valley

16:12.738 --> 16:16.800
because we wanted all of the
growers to negotiate together,

16:16.875 --> 16:18.604
but what disrupted that plan

16:18.677 --> 16:21.442
was when the Filipino workers
went out on strike.

16:21.513 --> 16:25.472
Because there was so much
violence against the Filipinos.

16:25.551 --> 16:28.145
They locked them in their
bunkhouses in the labor camps,

16:28.220 --> 16:30.086
they turned off the light, gas,
and the water.

16:30.155 --> 16:32.089
Some of them were beaten up.

16:32.157 --> 16:34.125
And so when these stories
came back to us,

16:34.193 --> 16:36.218
well, we thought we don't have
any option.

16:36.295 --> 16:38.286
So we joined forces
on the strike

16:38.364 --> 16:40.628
to support the Filipino workers.

16:40.699 --> 16:43.134
♪ This land is your land ♪

16:45.137 --> 16:46.764
♪ This land is my land ♪

16:50.809 --> 16:54.370
♪ From California ♪

16:54.446 --> 16:58.144
♪ To the New York island ♪

17:00.052 --> 17:03.420
♪ From the redwood forest ♪

17:03.489 --> 17:09.053
♪ To the Gulf Stream waters ♪

17:09.127 --> 17:11.654
♪ I tell you ♪

17:11.730 --> 17:16.998
♪ This land was made
for you and me ♪

17:20.705 --> 17:22.070
♪ As I went walking ♪

17:22.141 --> 17:24.269
<i>;Huelga, huelga!</i>

17:24.343 --> 17:25.833
That was an amazing thing

17:25.911 --> 17:28.005
for me, as a young Chicano,

17:28.079 --> 17:30.549
to suddenly come upon two people
in the field

17:30.616 --> 17:33.244
that were actually working
on a social problem

17:33.318 --> 17:35.082
that had affected my whole life.

17:35.154 --> 17:37.987
I saw them up close
and I had no problem

17:38.057 --> 17:40.025
believing that
I had to follow them.

17:40.092 --> 17:41.423
I had to become a follower.

17:41.493 --> 17:47.330
♪ Solidarity forever... ♪

17:47.399 --> 17:48.759
I was not an easy follower.

17:48.801 --> 17:50.166
I was pretty independent,

17:50.235 --> 17:52.636
but here suddenly is Cesar

17:52.704 --> 17:55.173
and here is Dolores.

17:55.240 --> 17:57.800
And I devoted all of my
energies, all of my waking hours

17:57.876 --> 17:59.435
to follow them into the cause.

18:02.147 --> 18:06.380
I too have the dream that
I learned from Dolores Huerta

18:06.452 --> 18:10.685
that farmworkers
can share in the wealth

18:10.756 --> 18:13.885
that they help to produce.

18:13.959 --> 18:15.654
She has such a firm belief

18:15.727 --> 18:18.162
in what she's doing

18:18.230 --> 18:20.995
that she infects you with it.

18:21.066 --> 18:22.363
Dolores Huerta.

18:29.608 --> 18:31.667
<i>Muchas gracias,
compafieros y compafieras.</i>

18:31.743 --> 18:34.041
Then I think
she looks deep within you

18:34.113 --> 18:36.548
and she understands
what you're capable of,

18:36.615 --> 18:38.049
that you actually can do more

18:38.117 --> 18:39.676
than what you thought
was possible.

18:40.886 --> 18:42.564
When we started
to organize farmworkers,

18:42.588 --> 18:45.250
people would say to us,
"They're poor,

18:45.324 --> 18:47.349
"they don't speak English,
they're not citizens.

18:47.426 --> 18:49.827
How are you going
to possibly organize them?"

18:49.895 --> 18:53.126
And of course the response
that we had to that is,

18:53.198 --> 18:56.691
"The power is in your body."

18:56.768 --> 18:57.929
<i>;Viva la cause!</i>

18:59.238 --> 19:00.238
<i>;Viva la huelgal.</i>

19:03.809 --> 19:06.073
One of the things that was
very helpful in the beginning

19:06.145 --> 19:07.544
was that Dolores being out there

19:07.613 --> 19:09.775
made it all right for women
to be in the picket line

19:09.848 --> 19:11.748
and so it made it all right
for the husbands

19:11.817 --> 19:13.945
to permit their wives
to be in the picket line,

19:14.019 --> 19:16.647
and their daughters,
and their mothers and so forth.

19:16.722 --> 19:19.384
We found that
it's a tremendous advantage

19:19.458 --> 19:22.792
to give women
equal participation in the union

19:22.861 --> 19:24.439
because, well, they're
tremendous resources there

19:24.463 --> 19:25.794
and they should be used.

19:25.864 --> 19:28.356
We had women
who ran the clinics.

19:28.433 --> 19:31.630
We had women as field directors.

19:31.703 --> 19:33.501
Women did a lot
of the clerical work.

19:33.572 --> 19:35.097
I remember hearing people
say to Cesar,

19:35.174 --> 19:36.539
"Why do you have so many women?"

19:36.608 --> 19:38.599
and he'd say,
"Because they do the work."

19:38.677 --> 19:40.702
Whether it be Dolores Huerta,

19:40.779 --> 19:42.042
Jessica Govea,

19:42.114 --> 19:43.411
or Helen Chavez,

19:43.482 --> 19:46.213
there were more women
involved in the UFW

19:46.285 --> 19:47.514
than probably every other

19:47.586 --> 19:50.419
labor union in the United States
combined.

19:50.489 --> 19:52.480
The one place
where we were lacking

19:52.558 --> 19:54.151
was on the executive board

19:54.226 --> 19:58.561
and for many, many years, I was
the only woman on the board.

19:58.630 --> 20:00.275
Cesar, you represent a culture

20:00.299 --> 20:02.597
that says the woman must be
protected at all costs,

20:02.668 --> 20:04.864
yet you take Dolores
right out in the picket line,

20:04.937 --> 20:06.063
into a demonstration.

20:06.138 --> 20:07.970
Do you ever worry
about her life?

20:08.040 --> 20:09.906
We worry, sure.

20:09.975 --> 20:12.637
There are some situations
that are very dangerous,

20:12.711 --> 20:15.408
but she's a leader of the union

20:15.480 --> 20:17.280
and those are the risks
that have to be taken.

20:18.383 --> 20:20.875
These were not small farmers.

20:20.953 --> 20:22.318
This was agribusiness,

20:22.387 --> 20:26.324
and the growers were tied
into local government

20:26.391 --> 20:29.361
and have control
of local sheriffs.

20:29.428 --> 20:32.728
So when we would go
on a picket line,

20:32.798 --> 20:36.666
the sheriffs would not hesitate
to beat somebody.

20:36.735 --> 20:40.569
The contractors or the foremen
or some of the tractor workers

20:40.639 --> 20:44.473
wouldn't hesitate
to run over a striker.

20:46.178 --> 20:48.613
I know of no grower
in the Delano area

20:48.680 --> 20:52.617
who has refused
or who would refuse

20:52.684 --> 20:57.520
to sit down and to talk
with the workers on his farm.

20:57.589 --> 20:59.489
But not with the
union organization.

20:59.558 --> 21:03.119
But they do not feel that
the organizer and the agitators

21:03.195 --> 21:04.959
represent their workers.

21:05.030 --> 21:10.093
We had been on strike
since September of 1965,

21:10.168 --> 21:11.465
and at the beginning,

21:11.536 --> 21:13.561
we had a lot of people
that brought donations,

21:13.639 --> 21:15.664
contributions
to keep the strike going,

21:15.741 --> 21:18.938
but as the months went on,
it was tapering off.

21:19.011 --> 21:21.605
So we knew we had to do
something different

21:21.680 --> 21:23.512
and that's when we came up
with the idea

21:23.582 --> 21:24.947
of doing the march
to Sacramento.

21:27.753 --> 21:30.085
The strikers
and their supporters

21:30.155 --> 21:31.623
is beyond question

21:31.690 --> 21:33.590
the largest and the most
significant gathering

21:33.659 --> 21:36.390
on behalf of the farmworkers
in California history.

21:39.631 --> 21:42.328
Along the march she
negotiated the Schenley contract,

21:42.401 --> 21:44.802
which was the first contract
in history

21:44.870 --> 21:50.001
between farmworkers
and the growers.

21:50.075 --> 21:53.045
Labor history has been made here
in California today,

21:53.111 --> 21:54.875
an agreement between

21:54.946 --> 21:56.880
the National Farm Workers
Association

21:56.948 --> 22:00.248
and the Schenley Industries
Corporation.

22:00.319 --> 22:02.447
Dolores Huerta negotiated

22:02.521 --> 22:04.148
my grandfather's
first union contract,

22:04.222 --> 22:07.715
and it was because of Dolores's
work that my grandpa was able

22:07.793 --> 22:11.457
to get water in the workplace.
Drinking water, toilets.

22:11.530 --> 22:14.295
LORI de LEON:
And her being a young Chicana,

22:14.366 --> 22:16.130
sitting at the table
facing the growers

22:16.201 --> 22:19.637
with farmworkers who were
primarily just Spanish-speaking,

22:19.705 --> 22:21.503
some of them illiterate,

22:21.573 --> 22:25.840
stayed with me throughout
my life how individuals,

22:25.911 --> 22:28.903
whether they can read, write,
or speak English or not,

22:28.980 --> 22:32.109
have individual power.

22:37.356 --> 22:40.917
If the rules
to settle our economic problems

22:40.992 --> 22:42.255
are not forthcoming,

22:42.327 --> 22:44.819
we will take economic pressures,

22:44.896 --> 22:47.194
strike, boycott,

22:47.265 --> 22:50.599
to force recognition and obtain
collective bargaining rights.

22:50.669 --> 22:54.105
The social and economic
revolution of the farmworkers

22:54.172 --> 22:55.640
is well underway,

22:55.707 --> 22:59.473
and it will not be stopped
until we receive equality.

22:59.544 --> 23:03.139
If Dolores
Huerta and Cesar Chavez

23:03.215 --> 23:06.014
felt it was possible

23:06.084 --> 23:07.848
to organize farmworkers

23:07.919 --> 23:12.117
when no one believed
that that was possible,

23:12.190 --> 23:13.316
it was because

23:13.392 --> 23:16.487
many of us during that period

23:16.561 --> 23:19.587
were totally convinced
that we could change the world.

23:19.664 --> 23:22.531
We were persuaded

23:22.601 --> 23:24.968
that revolutionary change
was possible.

23:27.205 --> 23:29.105
♪ Uh, with your bad self ♪

23:29.174 --> 23:30.801
♪ Say it loud ♪

23:30.876 --> 23:33.607
♪ I'm black and I'm proud! ♪

23:33.678 --> 23:35.806
♪ Say it loud ♪

23:35.881 --> 23:38.509
♪ I'm black and I'm proud! ♪

23:38.583 --> 23:40.223
♪ Some people say
we got a lot of malice ♪

23:40.252 --> 23:42.084
♪ Some say it's a lot of nerve ♪

23:42.154 --> 23:47.285
♪ But I say we won't quit moving
until we get what we deserve ♪

23:47.359 --> 23:48.724
This was in the '60s.

23:48.794 --> 23:50.762
The civil rights movement
was going on,

23:50.829 --> 23:52.388
the peace movement was going on,

23:52.464 --> 23:54.091
the feminist movement
was just starting,

23:54.166 --> 23:56.692
and the environmental movement
was just starting,

23:56.768 --> 23:58.759
and so you had this ambience
all around you

23:58.837 --> 24:01.067
that you could really
change the world.

24:01.139 --> 24:05.007
There was a lot
of electricity in the air.

24:05.076 --> 24:07.238
I mean, it was new.
People were like free.

24:07.312 --> 24:08.473
♪ Say it loud ♪

24:08.547 --> 24:10.311
♪ I'm black and I'm proud ♪

24:10.382 --> 24:13.094
It was electric, especially
when you walked past the fields

24:13.118 --> 24:15.951
and there was a lot of people
in the fields still working

24:16.021 --> 24:18.490
<i>"and people were marching
and say, "Vengan hermanos.</i>

24:18.557 --> 24:20.218
<i>Come on, come on,
Vengan, sélganse."</i>

24:20.292 --> 24:22.818
<i>Unanse con HOSOUOS.</i>

24:22.894 --> 24:24.639
And people would actually
come out of the fields.

24:24.663 --> 24:26.654
♪ Now we demand a chance ♪

24:26.731 --> 24:29.063
♪ To do things for ourselves ♪

24:29.134 --> 24:31.501
It became really
apparent that the racism

24:31.570 --> 24:32.980
that touches black people
is no different

24:33.004 --> 24:35.098
than the racism that touches
the other groups,

24:35.173 --> 24:36.918
and so we were really marching
for everybody.

24:36.942 --> 24:39.673
We were marching
for social change.

24:39.744 --> 24:43.806
Oftentimes today looking back,

24:43.882 --> 24:46.180
we think about discrete
and distinct movements.

24:46.251 --> 24:48.196
We think that the black movement
was one movement,

24:48.220 --> 24:50.018
and then the Chicano movement
was over here,

24:50.088 --> 24:52.716
and then there was
the Native American movement.

24:52.791 --> 24:54.190
But all of those movements,

24:54.259 --> 24:56.819
and the individuals
within those movements,

24:56.895 --> 25:00.593
were connected,
and we knew that one movement

25:00.665 --> 25:03.635
would not be successful
without the other.

25:03.702 --> 25:07.195
Today we talk about the
intersectionality of struggles,

25:07.272 --> 25:10.640
but I think during that period
we actually lived it.

25:10.709 --> 25:12.507
We experienced it.

25:12.577 --> 25:15.308
If you remain truly nonviolent,

25:15.380 --> 25:17.747
and I'm pledging my support...

25:17.816 --> 25:20.786
We come today
to lend our moral support,

25:20.852 --> 25:22.547
our fiscal support,

25:22.621 --> 25:23.918
and our financial support

25:23.989 --> 25:26.321
to the efforts of Cesar Chavez.

25:28.126 --> 25:30.561
There was a
lot of passion in all of us

25:30.629 --> 25:32.119
for what we were doing.

25:32.197 --> 25:34.188
I mean, we were making
five dollars a week

25:34.266 --> 25:35.495
in terms of salary, right?

25:35.567 --> 25:39.197
That was more than just the
union not having the resources.

25:39.271 --> 25:41.035
It didn't.

25:41.106 --> 25:44.406
It was also because there was
no way you could pay people

25:44.476 --> 25:45.773
to work seven days a week.

25:45.844 --> 25:48.279
You know,
it had to come from your heart.

25:48.346 --> 25:51.441
I remember
Dolores calling and saying,

25:51.516 --> 25:53.041
"Well, why don't you
come work for us?"

25:53.118 --> 25:54.643
I said, "Well, how much
does it pay?"

25:54.719 --> 25:57.086
"Five dollars a week
and all you can eat."

25:57.155 --> 25:59.487
I said, "I don't think my father
will appreciate that"

25:59.558 --> 26:01.424
"having helped me get through
law school

26:01.493 --> 26:03.894
and going back
to where they left."

26:03.962 --> 26:06.488
And of course, I said yes.

26:06.565 --> 26:10.126
And my father was angry because
he thought it was regressive.

26:10.201 --> 26:14.331
In reality,
it was a most trans...

26:14.406 --> 26:16.966
(voice breaking}: Formative
period in my life.

26:24.916 --> 26:27.817
We wish to welcome you
to Delano.

26:27.886 --> 26:30.355
You know, and I don't
have to tell you this,

26:30.422 --> 26:33.915
how thankful we are for the
gifts that you have brought us.

26:33.992 --> 26:37.895
You also know that the gifts
of food and clothing

26:37.963 --> 26:41.991
are the things that will keep us
alive for the next few months.

26:42.067 --> 26:44.229
Dolores, if someone just came in

26:44.302 --> 26:45.895
and put $5,000 in your lap

26:45.971 --> 26:48.211
and said, "I want you to spend
this totally on yourself",

26:48.239 --> 26:50.765
Dolores, nobody else,"
what would you do with it?

26:50.842 --> 26:53.903
Well, I would...

26:53.979 --> 26:55.723
I'd turn around
and contribute it to the union.

26:55.747 --> 26:57.215
That's what I would do.

26:57.282 --> 26:58.613
No fair.

26:58.683 --> 27:00.227
Because that would be spending
it on myself,

27:00.251 --> 27:01.980
because to me,
this is my life's work.

27:02.053 --> 27:04.954
To me, you know,
this is the reason I live.

27:05.023 --> 27:07.720
But don't you ever have
the average woman's dream

27:07.792 --> 27:11.126
of going out to some spa,
and being relaxed,

27:11.196 --> 27:13.358
and having a new hairdo,
and buying a great dress,

27:13.431 --> 27:15.263
and having a big party?

27:15.333 --> 27:20.169
Well, to me, having a hairdo
and being in a spa

27:20.238 --> 27:22.138
would be a terrible
waste of time.

27:25.210 --> 27:28.271
My uncle,
Cesar Chavez, and my mother

27:28.346 --> 27:32.112
were both greatly influenced
by the philosophies of Gandhi.

27:32.183 --> 27:34.948
You can't help people
unless you live like them.

27:35.020 --> 27:37.512
So, we're not going to be able
to help organize farmworkers

27:37.589 --> 27:39.455
unless we live
like the farmworkers.

27:39.524 --> 27:42.789
My mother and Cesar
ingrained themselves in the community

27:42.861 --> 27:44.761
and they lived
in those communities.

27:44.829 --> 27:46.923
They didn't fly in
from Washington or San Francisco

27:46.998 --> 27:48.776
or L.A. to say, "We know it all
and we're going"

27:48.800 --> 27:51.201
to teach you guys
how to build a union."

27:51.269 --> 27:53.931
They said, "We need to build
an association"

27:54.005 --> 27:57.805
that addresses the day-to-day
needs of folks.

28:00.145 --> 28:02.807
I only knew growing up

28:02.881 --> 28:05.509
that when we were poor,
because we were,

28:05.583 --> 28:08.553
my mom would always tell us,
"You're poor by choice."

28:08.620 --> 28:11.817
We have a tendency to want to be
too comfortable, you know.

28:11.890 --> 28:14.484
And I'm trying to educate
my children

28:14.559 --> 28:16.357
in the way that I'm raising them

28:16.428 --> 28:18.487
to give their lives
to work for other people.

28:18.563 --> 28:21.191
And I'm hoping that
out of the 11 that I've got,

28:21.266 --> 28:23.428
I sure ought to come out
with a pretty good percentage.

28:23.501 --> 28:25.128
We didn't get it at the time,

28:25.203 --> 28:27.729
the lessons that she was trying
to teach us and, in fact,

28:27.806 --> 28:29.399
we were like most teenagers,

28:29.474 --> 28:31.966
rebellious and angry

28:32.043 --> 28:34.478
about her ideas of materialism.

28:34.546 --> 28:37.846
Our biggest dream was just to be
like the kids at school

28:37.916 --> 28:39.645
who had all the latest fashions,

28:39.718 --> 28:42.881
but we didn't get
any of that stuff.

28:42.954 --> 28:44.922
So we knew we were outside
of the norm for sure.

28:44.989 --> 28:46.548
Why are you here today?

28:46.624 --> 28:49.423
Because I don't like the people
that are here in our town,

28:49.494 --> 28:50.984
they don't belong here,

28:51.062 --> 28:53.074
and I wish they'd all go back
to where they came from.

28:53.098 --> 28:54.775
Now, which people are these
you're talking about?

28:54.799 --> 28:58.030
I'm talking about the outsiders
that have come into this strike

28:58.103 --> 29:01.129
and have interfered
with our daily workers.

29:01.206 --> 29:05.074
Our workers are loyal workers
and they work out in the fields

29:05.143 --> 29:06.804
and yet they are harassed.

29:06.878 --> 29:08.505
They're insulted.

29:08.580 --> 29:09.843
We've had no trouble.

29:09.914 --> 29:11.882
Well, now, are you unhappy
at the labor troubles?

29:11.950 --> 29:14.078
We had no labor troubles!

29:29.167 --> 29:32.865
Senator Kennedy
actively gave his backing

29:32.937 --> 29:35.463
to the unionization campaign.

29:35.540 --> 29:37.065
I think people are frustrated,

29:37.142 --> 29:40.043
and I think they're terribly
disturbed by the fact

29:40.111 --> 29:42.102
that they haven't had
more success,

29:42.180 --> 29:44.080
and that the federal government
in Washington

29:44.149 --> 29:46.550
has not been helpful to them,

29:46.618 --> 29:49.883
and that the state
has not been helpful to them.

29:49.954 --> 29:53.015
I remember my grandpa
telling me how important it was

29:53.091 --> 29:55.321
to the Latino community here
in California

29:55.393 --> 29:58.920
that Robert Kennedy came in
and stood with them

29:58.997 --> 30:01.022
when the sheriff
and police department

30:01.099 --> 30:05.536
were actually arresting these
people for doing lawful things.

30:05.603 --> 30:07.071
If I have reason to believe

30:07.138 --> 30:08.936
that there's going to be
a riot started

30:09.007 --> 30:11.271
and somebody tells me
that there's going to be trouble

30:11.342 --> 30:13.538
if you don't stop them,
then it's my duty to stop them.

30:13.611 --> 30:15.739
Then you go out and arrest them?

30:15.814 --> 30:16.975
Absolutely.

30:17.048 --> 30:18.345
How can you go arrest somebody

30:18.416 --> 30:20.248
if they haven't
violated the law?

30:20.318 --> 30:21.752
They're ready
to violate the law.

30:21.820 --> 30:22.981
In other words...

30:26.257 --> 30:28.555
Could I suggest in the interim
period of time,

30:28.626 --> 30:30.025
in the luncheon period of time,

30:30.094 --> 30:32.119
that the sheriff
and the district attorney

30:32.197 --> 30:34.962
read the Constitution
of the United States?

30:37.769 --> 30:39.079
To see this Harvard-educated guy

30:39.103 --> 30:42.232
from Massachusetts
talk in a funny accent,

30:42.307 --> 30:44.639
stand with us,
it meant something.

30:44.709 --> 30:49.237
You can't imagine a
political figure of that station

30:49.314 --> 30:54.252
these days going after
corporations with that vigor.

30:54.319 --> 30:55.480
For who?

30:55.553 --> 30:57.078
Not for his own.

30:57.155 --> 30:58.589
Not even on his coast.

30:58.656 --> 30:59.817
Wow, right?

30:59.891 --> 31:02.053
We have somebody
of national prominence

31:02.126 --> 31:03.594
who knows who we are,

31:03.661 --> 31:06.961
and who's running for president
and has a chance to win.

31:07.031 --> 31:10.365
We all went and worked on his
campaign throughout the state.

31:10.435 --> 31:12.335
The farmworkers pioneered

31:12.403 --> 31:14.735
a voter outreach strategy
to Latino voters

31:14.806 --> 31:18.401
that had never been done before
anywhere in the United States.

31:18.476 --> 31:21.104
Labor's idea of mobilizing
for an election

31:21.179 --> 31:23.511
was to write a check
to the local Democrat.

31:23.581 --> 31:25.982
It was the farmworker folks
in California

31:26.050 --> 31:28.781
who were knocking on doors,
persuading them to vote,

31:28.853 --> 31:30.685
registering them at the door,

31:30.755 --> 31:32.723
all the things
Democrats nationally

31:32.790 --> 31:33.951
are dependent on today.

31:34.025 --> 31:36.255
There were hundreds of us.

31:36.327 --> 31:38.728
Every door we knocked on,
we knew we were going to win.

31:38.796 --> 31:39.956
You could just taste victory.

31:45.169 --> 31:48.605
We came back for the party
and we had the TV set up

31:48.673 --> 31:51.301
and, you know, I could see my
mother on the television screen

31:51.376 --> 31:53.970
next to Kennedy and him
acknowledging the farmworkers.

31:54.045 --> 31:57.675
For them and all of those
Mexican-Americans

31:57.749 --> 32:00.184
who were such supporters
of mine.

32:01.653 --> 32:04.122
And Dolores Huerta,
who is an old friend of mine,

32:04.188 --> 32:05.622
and who is working
with the union,

32:05.690 --> 32:07.749
to thank her and tell her
how much I appreciate

32:07.825 --> 32:09.224
her coming tonight.

32:09.294 --> 32:11.524
We have certain obligations
and responsibilities

32:11.596 --> 32:14.361
to our fellow citizens,
which we talked about

32:14.432 --> 32:16.127
during the course
of this campaign.

32:16.200 --> 32:18.100
And I want to make it clear

32:18.169 --> 32:19.914
that if I'm elected president
of the United States,

32:19.938 --> 32:22.066
with your help,
I intend to keep them.

32:25.543 --> 32:27.773
Now it's on to Chicago,
and let's win there.

32:27.845 --> 32:29.176
Thank you very much.

33:16.728 --> 33:21.791
I had never before
experienced the death of the future.

33:21.866 --> 33:23.493
The death of the past, yes,

33:23.568 --> 33:27.527
but when the future dies,
it's different.

33:32.744 --> 33:34.007
All this hope,

33:34.078 --> 33:35.978
the one person
that would actually

33:36.047 --> 33:38.345
stand up for us is gone.

33:42.587 --> 33:45.887
Some people became very cynical
after Robert Kennedy was killed,

33:45.957 --> 33:49.222
but we had to continue
to keep on working for justice

33:49.293 --> 33:51.819
and nonviolence because

33:51.896 --> 33:55.332
that's what Robert Kennedy
would have wanted us to do.

33:56.901 --> 33:59.836
Dolores was the
closest one to Senator Kennedy,

33:59.904 --> 34:04.569
and having been witness to
something as terrifying as that

34:04.642 --> 34:10.842
made her understanding of
nonviolence even more important,

34:10.915 --> 34:16.478
because she saw firsthand the
impact that violence can have.

34:18.389 --> 34:22.121
Hatred and racism
are extensions of violence,

34:22.193 --> 34:25.686
and if we become that which
we are trying to end,

34:25.763 --> 34:28.322
then you know, we are becoming
like the oppressor then,

34:28.399 --> 34:30.833
and we're trying to set up
a different system.

34:50.288 --> 34:52.085
To talk about grapes and lettuce

34:52.156 --> 34:54.123
produced in poverty
and suffering

34:54.192 --> 34:56.456
felt like the first step.

34:56.527 --> 35:00.225
An additional step was
to talk about grapes and lettuce

35:00.298 --> 35:01.663
produced in poisons.

35:03.334 --> 35:05.701
And 90,000 people
were poisoned last year.

35:05.770 --> 35:08.398
A thousand people
were killed last year.

35:08.473 --> 35:11.443
And then people say,
"Where at? In Vietnam?"

35:11.509 --> 35:14.103
And I say, "No, in the fields of
the United States of America."

35:14.178 --> 35:18.172
The pesticides that
were sprayed in those fields,

35:18.249 --> 35:19.410
we never knew what it was

35:19.484 --> 35:22.112
and there were so many times

35:22.186 --> 35:23.745
we wound up
stumbling out of the fields

35:23.821 --> 35:27.519
because our eyes were watering,
our skin was irritated.

35:27.592 --> 35:32.189
You could just see the splotches
on your skin.

35:32.263 --> 35:34.493
It's toxic.

35:34.565 --> 35:37.193
It's poisonous and people die.

35:40.371 --> 35:44.001
Earlimart, McFarland, Delano,
all those areas

35:44.075 --> 35:47.170
have been affected by the use
of pesticides since World War II

35:47.245 --> 35:49.213
and they become cancer clusters,

35:49.280 --> 35:52.341
little kids born with limbs
that are misshapen.

35:52.416 --> 35:56.011
They don't have them, you know?

35:56.087 --> 35:58.749
This is the unspeakable stuff
that the United Farm Workers

35:58.823 --> 36:00.882
tried to fight against.

36:00.958 --> 36:05.623
The farmworkers
were a living daily reminder

36:05.696 --> 36:08.324
and warning system

36:08.399 --> 36:12.632
of what everyone
was going to experience.

36:12.703 --> 36:14.762
What appeal would
you make to a consumer,

36:14.839 --> 36:18.742
you know, a mother who's
concerned about her children?

36:18.809 --> 36:20.420
This is
definitely a flag to them

36:20.444 --> 36:22.003
to say there's something wrong

36:22.079 --> 36:24.707
with the poisons that are on our
food that they eat every day.

36:27.351 --> 36:30.514
Well, we have the many cases,
many affidavits of cases

36:30.588 --> 36:33.387
where workers have been poisoned
by pesticides,

36:33.457 --> 36:34.737
where they have
serious illnesses

36:34.792 --> 36:38.592
and also there's, of course,
many reports of deaths

36:38.663 --> 36:40.631
that have been caused
by pesticides.

36:40.698 --> 36:43.531
But isn't that just
sort of an occupational hazard?

36:43.601 --> 36:45.626
Is there anything
that can be done about it?

36:45.703 --> 36:48.263
Well, we believe that something
can be done about this

36:48.339 --> 36:50.433
but, of course,
in order to do this

36:50.508 --> 36:52.567
we have to have the cooperation
of the employers.

36:52.643 --> 36:57.809
In the 19605, labor
was seen as anti-environmental.

36:57.882 --> 37:02.046
Well, here's the farmworkers
in the vanguard.

37:02.119 --> 37:03.245
They won.

37:03.321 --> 37:05.653
They got DDT banned.

37:05.723 --> 37:09.182
They founded the whole idea
of environmental justice.

37:09.260 --> 37:11.456
Older environmental groups

37:11.529 --> 37:14.362
often were concerned
with the redwoods,

37:14.432 --> 37:17.333
they were concerned
with the trees, not the people.

37:17.401 --> 37:21.702
It was Dolores, among others,
who made this linkage

37:21.772 --> 37:26.369
by making people
look at the human cost.

37:26.444 --> 37:27.754
The environmental
justice movement

37:27.778 --> 37:29.371
said that certain
environmental hazards

37:29.447 --> 37:31.677
are disproportionately impacted
on people of color.

37:31.749 --> 37:34.184
That would never be allowed
if these people

37:34.252 --> 37:35.583
were white middle class.

37:35.653 --> 37:38.315
So it wasn't simply
stopping DDT,

37:38.389 --> 37:40.084
but it was also making
the larger point

37:40.157 --> 37:42.626
you're only allowing this
because of who the workers are

37:42.693 --> 37:45.856
and their racial and class
background.

37:52.270 --> 37:56.867
The farmworker movement in
many ways was a cultural revolution

37:56.941 --> 37:59.967
because when people saw the
farmworkers come out on strike

38:00.044 --> 38:01.512
and go on those marches,

38:01.579 --> 38:03.513
I think that it really
said to people

38:03.581 --> 38:06.607
if the farmworkers can do this,
so can we.

38:06.684 --> 38:11.588
It gave our Latino people a
certain pride in who they were.

38:11.656 --> 38:16.822
We are Indio, Mestigo,
Hispano, Mexicano.

38:16.894 --> 38:20.262
The names have all been changed
across the centuries,

38:20.331 --> 38:22.698
but they all mean
the same thing.

38:22.767 --> 38:26.931
We have been Americanos
longer than America has existed.

38:27.004 --> 38:29.268
We are Aztlén!

39:07.345 --> 39:10.076
<i>♪ Oye coma va ♪</i>

39:10.147 --> 39:11.308
<i>♪ Mi ritmo ♪</i>

39:11.382 --> 39:13.316
<i>♪ Bueno pa gozar' ♪</i>

39:13.384 --> 39:15.045
<i>♪ Mulata' ♪</i>

39:20.224 --> 39:22.989
First time I
opened up Time magazine,

39:23.060 --> 39:25.688
a little picture of a march

39:25.763 --> 39:28.596
and all the people out there
looked like me.

39:28.666 --> 39:31.533
That first impact was huge.

39:31.602 --> 39:34.594
So, the farmworker movement
was a catalyst

39:34.672 --> 39:39.508
and ignited a personal and
community-wide self-evaluation

39:39.577 --> 39:41.739
of who we were as a people.

39:41.812 --> 39:43.623
Yeah, I can
remember seeing those marches,

39:43.647 --> 39:45.809
and it was kind of amazing
for a brown boy

39:45.883 --> 39:50.320
to see a bunch of brown people
in the United States

39:50.388 --> 39:53.119
marching in simultaneity
about something.

39:53.190 --> 39:57.320
As a Latino kid, the pressure
to assimilate was great.

39:57.395 --> 39:59.989
Seeing women like Dolores Huerta
out there

40:00.064 --> 40:02.158
gave me an example
as a young brown kid

40:02.233 --> 40:04.065
to be able to engage in a way

40:04.135 --> 40:07.002
that's not white,
that was actually particular

40:07.071 --> 40:08.766
to us as brown people
in this country.

40:46.010 --> 40:48.001
Even though I grew up

40:48.078 --> 40:49.944
in such this strong
Chicano movement,

40:50.014 --> 40:53.279
the television
and all of the media messages

40:53.350 --> 40:55.785
told me everything the opposite,

40:55.853 --> 41:00.882
that brown was ugly,
being poor was bad.

41:03.594 --> 41:06.723
She knew that we were
going to be experiencing persecution

41:06.797 --> 41:08.526
based on the color of our skin

41:08.599 --> 41:10.260
and so she was constantly
telling us

41:10.334 --> 41:13.304
how beautiful our dark skin was.

41:13.370 --> 41:15.600
In high school,
I started talking about,

41:15.673 --> 41:17.163
"I want a nose job
for graduation.

41:17.241 --> 41:19.121
That's what I want
my graduation present to be,"

41:19.176 --> 41:22.009
as if we could afford that,
but that was my thing.

41:22.079 --> 41:23.012
I wanted a nose job.

41:23.080 --> 41:25.549
She was like, "Over my dead body"

41:25.616 --> 41:28.711
"will you ever reconstruct
that beautiful nose

41:28.786 --> 41:30.754
"that God and your ancestors,

41:30.821 --> 41:32.915
"your Tarahumara tribe
has given you.

41:32.990 --> 41:35.084
You will not touch that nose
ever."

41:39.897 --> 41:41.524
Revolution starts

41:41.599 --> 41:44.466
with self-love in the sense

41:44.535 --> 41:46.246
that if you're a member
of an oppressed people,

41:46.270 --> 41:50.264
an oppressed class, you have
to develop self-respect,

41:50.341 --> 41:54.835
and that starts by developing
some affection for who you are.

41:59.049 --> 42:01.177
You love your family
and you say,

42:01.252 --> 42:03.949
"Okay, but why does the world
regard them as inferior?

42:04.021 --> 42:06.285
"Why does the world regard them
as ugly when, in my eyes,

42:06.357 --> 42:09.884
they're quite beautiful?"

42:09.960 --> 42:14.830
Movements not only affect laws,

42:14.899 --> 42:18.563
they also affect
the way people feel.

42:18.636 --> 42:20.866
They affect emotions.

42:25.042 --> 42:26.753
Well, then, is
this more a social movement?

42:26.777 --> 42:28.575
It's both.
You can't separate it.

42:28.646 --> 42:31.274
It's both a labor movement
and a social movement

42:31.348 --> 42:32.611
or you can say it another way.

42:32.683 --> 42:34.310
I think all of
the labor movement

42:34.385 --> 42:35.910
has also been a social movement.

42:40.324 --> 42:42.520
This might sound kind of corny,

42:42.593 --> 42:46.223
but you have to really
love people, you know,

42:46.297 --> 42:48.356
to want to teach them,

42:48.432 --> 42:50.025
to want to have them grow.

42:50.100 --> 42:52.312
Because you're giving a lot of
yourself when you're doing that.

42:52.336 --> 42:55.271
It's not just filling out the
form and filling out the paper.

42:55.339 --> 42:57.099
When a farmworker comes in
with this problem,

42:57.141 --> 42:58.802
and then you're going to start
telling him

42:58.876 --> 43:01.277
the history of his abuse
and start getting him angry,

43:01.345 --> 43:03.507
that's going to take something
out of you right there,

43:03.581 --> 43:05.777
you know?

43:05.849 --> 43:08.079
She was so
dedicated to the work,

43:08.152 --> 43:11.713
like a workaholic,
that she felt guilty

43:11.789 --> 43:15.817
taking time
to enjoy life herself.

43:15.893 --> 43:19.523
So going to a jazz concert,
music, dance,

43:19.597 --> 43:22.032
which was her passion,

43:22.099 --> 43:24.693
she felt very guilty
about doing those things

43:24.768 --> 43:27.897
and she said that
it was my dad, Richard,

43:27.972 --> 43:30.066
who actually helped her

43:30.140 --> 43:33.303
look at life
a little bit differently.

43:33.377 --> 43:36.438
Richard was very good
to the kids in the family.

43:36.513 --> 43:39.813
He had a very loving nature.

43:39.883 --> 43:41.428
Of course, I wouldn't say
Richard was a feminist,

43:41.452 --> 43:43.750
but Richard was a great cook.

43:45.189 --> 43:47.886
We consider you part of us,
and us part of you.

43:47.958 --> 43:50.450
You brought Dolores
along to organize the union

43:50.527 --> 43:52.825
and to be a business partner

43:52.896 --> 43:55.263
and now she's living with
your brother, so it's family.

43:55.332 --> 43:56.493
Were you expecting that?

43:56.567 --> 43:58.535
No, I certainly wasn't.

43:58.602 --> 43:59.831
No.

43:59.903 --> 44:01.894
Life is all an accident,
you know?

44:01.972 --> 44:04.998
Sometimes those things
can't be foreseen.

44:07.478 --> 44:11.108
When my mother and my
father, Richard Chavez, got together,

44:11.181 --> 44:14.742
my father was still married
to another woman.

44:14.818 --> 44:16.115
And, of course,

44:16.186 --> 44:17.813
this is my version
that I like to believe

44:17.888 --> 44:20.186
to make myself feel better
as a love child.

44:21.992 --> 44:24.893
I've been called a bastard
by some,

44:24.962 --> 44:28.364
but I believe that my father
was in an unhappy marriage.

44:28.432 --> 44:31.561
At some point, my father
couldn't be there anymore.

44:31.635 --> 44:32.796
He met the love of his life.

44:32.870 --> 44:34.235
I don't know what happened.

44:34.304 --> 44:35.430
I wasn't there.

44:35.506 --> 44:37.031
I was just conceived.

44:37.107 --> 44:39.439
And of course, I didn't start
learning this stuff

44:39.510 --> 44:42.445
until we were older,
but there was always kind of

44:42.513 --> 44:44.481
a negative feeling
against my mom.

44:46.316 --> 44:49.513
What particularly
about Dolores upsets people?

44:49.586 --> 44:52.612
Well, it's her personal life,

44:52.690 --> 44:54.010
all the children
without marriage,

44:54.058 --> 44:57.221
and just one every year or so
is not accepted,

44:57.294 --> 45:02.164
and I think most of us
feel the same way.

45:02.232 --> 45:07.170
She did put up
with a lot of ridicule from people

45:07.237 --> 45:10.696
who wanted to see her
in a more traditional role,

45:10.774 --> 45:14.608
by the men who were threatened
by her power

45:14.678 --> 45:16.442
and her assertiveness.

45:16.513 --> 45:19.813
She cries, you know,
she rolls down the tears,

45:19.883 --> 45:22.079
you know,
and I'm all for the Chicano

45:22.152 --> 45:23.745
and all that
and like it's a joke.

45:23.821 --> 45:25.255
Like everybody knows
that the UFW,

45:25.322 --> 45:26.915
that's why they keep her
in Sacramento,

45:26.990 --> 45:28.719
and that's why they keep her
in Washington,

45:28.792 --> 45:30.089
keep them out of their hair,

45:30.160 --> 45:33.323
because she just likes to talk
a hell of a lot.

45:33.397 --> 45:34.674
While you guys are trying
to stop the money,

45:34.698 --> 45:36.097
we have to keep a lot going.

45:36.166 --> 45:39.397
How do you answer
the criticism of detractors

45:39.470 --> 45:41.939
who say that you have been
married and divorced twice,

45:42.005 --> 45:44.633
that you have 11 children
sprinkled over two marriages,

45:44.708 --> 45:46.938
and one relationship
with Richard Chavez,

45:47.010 --> 45:48.478
to whom you're not married?

45:48.545 --> 45:52.413
I guess there's not much
of an answer I can give to that.

45:52.483 --> 45:55.248
You know, I could probably say,
"Well, maybe I shouldn't

45:55.319 --> 45:57.515
have had the children,"
but I don't believe that.

45:57.588 --> 46:00.421
I think that a relationship
should bear children.

46:00.491 --> 46:03.517
Now, the thing is,
who maintains these kids?

46:03.594 --> 46:05.119
Who takes care of them?

46:05.195 --> 46:08.426
Who supports them if she's out
on these adventures?

46:08.499 --> 46:10.695
We were told...
Remember in the beginning,

46:10.768 --> 46:12.361
one of the criticisms was that,

46:12.436 --> 46:14.180
"You don't know what
you're doing to your families.

46:14.204 --> 46:16.070
"When they grow up,
they're going to disown you

46:16.140 --> 46:18.418
"and they'll really hate you
because you're not giving them

46:18.442 --> 46:21.878
the things that ordinary
children would like to have."

46:21.945 --> 46:24.209
Do you think the
children ever resent you

46:24.281 --> 46:26.443
because you're always so busy
with the organization?

46:26.517 --> 46:28.884
Oh definitely, they wouldn't be
human if they didn't.

46:28.952 --> 46:32.286
Of course, that lends
for a lot of friction,

46:32.356 --> 46:34.882
which, you know,
we always have to work out.

46:34.958 --> 46:37.427
The hardest thing for my
children has been the absences.

46:43.667 --> 46:46.364
LORI de LEON:
She was always gone.

46:46.436 --> 46:47.995
It wasn't a 9-to-5 job.

46:48.071 --> 46:50.267
She was, you know,
gone before we got up.

46:50.340 --> 46:52.672
We'd have to get ourselves ready
to go to school

46:52.743 --> 46:55.075
and try to find something
to eat.

46:56.980 --> 47:00.314
A lot of my mom's absences
had some positives and negatives.

47:00.384 --> 47:02.328
I dropped out of high school
and my mom didn't find out

47:02.352 --> 47:05.253
until ten months later,
you know, so.

47:11.094 --> 47:13.392
We were spending the night
in people's homes

47:13.463 --> 47:14.988
that we didn't know.

47:15.065 --> 47:18.467
We were going to labor camps
and not knowing if somebody

47:18.535 --> 47:21.300
was going to shoot at us,
as they did many times.

47:24.842 --> 47:28.301
It was very hard,
<i>I'll</i> be honest with you.

47:28.378 --> 47:30.608
Tough.

47:30.681 --> 47:35.243
LORI de LEON: The movement
became her most important child.

47:35.319 --> 47:37.845
I realize the importance
of the work,

47:37.921 --> 47:41.016
but I was also
very jealous of it.

47:41.091 --> 47:44.152
So... there's scars there.

47:44.228 --> 47:46.629
You know, there's scars there
because of that.

47:50.734 --> 47:52.412
When she was
around, we were just like

47:52.436 --> 47:54.598
soaking in as much
as we could of her

47:54.671 --> 47:56.935
because we just knew
she was going to be gone again.

48:00.477 --> 48:03.003
It was really difficult.

48:13.690 --> 48:17.991
It was really difficult
not to have my mom around,

48:18.061 --> 48:20.393
especially when you would see
your friends

48:20.464 --> 48:24.264
and how involved
their mothers were.

48:24.334 --> 48:28.635
There's something about
a mother's love, you know,

48:28.705 --> 48:29.934
and attention.

48:30.007 --> 48:31.406
So it was hard.

48:31.475 --> 48:35.503
There were a lot of very
difficult nights...

48:35.579 --> 48:37.172
and months.

48:39.249 --> 48:41.650
I lived
with a woman in Bakersfield

48:41.718 --> 48:44.278
for a few years
while my mom went to New York,

48:44.354 --> 48:46.755
but when my mom
came back for me,

48:46.823 --> 48:48.222
I didn't want to go with her

48:48.292 --> 48:51.159
because I liked my new home.

48:51.228 --> 48:52.593
There was stability.

48:52.663 --> 48:55.826
I had meals every time
I was supposed to have a meal.

48:55.899 --> 48:58.061
I mean eventually,
I did go back with her,

48:58.135 --> 48:59.796
but I remember crying
and feeling like,

48:59.870 --> 49:02.362
"This was my new home,"
you know.

49:02.439 --> 49:08.003
And then getting older and being
like, "Why was I left there?"

49:08.078 --> 49:11.673
Obviously, that has an impact
on a child's psyche.

49:13.483 --> 49:16.248
You know, but as I look back
at it, I'm like I understand it.

49:16.320 --> 49:18.084
I fully understand it.

49:18.155 --> 49:20.487
You know, it's like I know
there's brothers and sisters

49:20.557 --> 49:25.290
that have the same experiences,
but maybe they weren't so lucky

49:25.362 --> 49:29.230
to be placed in a loving home.

49:29.299 --> 49:32.997
You know, but that's part
of the sacrifice...

49:33.070 --> 49:35.698
That we
made and that we had to make.

49:41.712 --> 49:44.409
And we've all learned
that we're not afraid to struggle,

49:44.481 --> 49:46.279
we're not afraid to sacrifice,

49:46.350 --> 49:48.910
because you can't make change
if you're not willing

49:48.986 --> 49:50.249
to give something up.

49:50.320 --> 49:52.152
You've got to give up
some comfort.

49:52.222 --> 49:54.213
You've got to give up some time,

49:54.291 --> 49:56.385
and then we can see
the changes come.

49:57.794 --> 50:00.161
Not every woman is going
to take the kind of risks

50:00.230 --> 50:01.459
that I took with my children,

50:01.531 --> 50:03.226
you know,
what they had to go through,

50:03.300 --> 50:05.667
and I wouldn't really
want to wish it on any child

50:05.736 --> 50:07.329
or on any other woman.

50:07.404 --> 50:10.965
What I did in terms
of sacrificing my children,

50:11.041 --> 50:13.009
I know it was very painful
for them,

50:13.076 --> 50:15.511
and it still pains me
when I think about it.

50:19.783 --> 50:24.516
And yet, I
also feel very, very strongly

50:24.588 --> 50:27.580
that she felt she was giving
them so much more

50:27.657 --> 50:31.218
than what she was asking them
to sacrifice.

50:31.294 --> 50:34.355
She was giving them
meaningful lives,

50:34.431 --> 50:39.198
which is something that is
very, very rare in this society.

50:41.338 --> 50:43.383
You've got
to have some kind of faith,

50:43.407 --> 50:45.808
you know, if you're going to be
walking away from your kids

50:45.876 --> 50:50.780
like that, you know, and leaving
your families like that.

50:50.847 --> 50:52.144
You've got to believe

50:52.215 --> 50:54.980
in something bigger than you,
you know?

51:11.701 --> 51:14.227
Grape-picking may
be a California problem,

51:14.304 --> 51:16.102
but the United Farm Workers
are determined

51:16.173 --> 51:17.732
to let New Yorkers
know about it.

51:17.808 --> 51:19.674
♪ Bang bang ♪

51:22.345 --> 51:24.143
♪ Bang bang ♪

51:25.949 --> 51:27.314
♪ Bang bang ♪

51:30.587 --> 51:34.080
In the strike, we
were not able to succeed

51:34.157 --> 51:35.886
because the growers
refused to negotiate.

51:35.959 --> 51:39.259
They could just bring in
strike breakers continuously.

51:39.329 --> 51:42.196
So we really had to think about
what other options we had

51:42.265 --> 51:44.927
and it was actually an attorney
from San Francisco

51:45.001 --> 51:46.332
and he said to us,

51:46.403 --> 51:48.929
"Have you ever thought
of trying to boycott?"

51:50.807 --> 51:52.400
We had boycott committees

51:52.476 --> 51:55.468
in Detroit, and Chicago,
and New York City,

51:55.545 --> 51:57.809
and San Francisco,
and then in other cities

51:57.881 --> 52:00.441
throughout the country,
including Canada and Europe.

52:00.517 --> 52:03.248
I was in charge
of the New York boycott,

52:03.320 --> 52:05.812
and I remember speaking
at Madison Square Garden

52:05.889 --> 52:09.553
and they told me I had
60 seconds to deliver my message

52:09.626 --> 52:12.721
and my message was,
"farmworkers are on strike.

52:12.796 --> 52:15.424
"Don't buy grapes.

52:15.499 --> 52:17.900
Don't shop at stores
that have grapes."

52:17.968 --> 52:19.595
That was it.

52:19.669 --> 52:23.230
What first comes
to mind is what Dolores modeled,

52:23.306 --> 52:26.435
which was to go out
and meet new people,

52:26.510 --> 52:31.676
and make those connections
about this struggle for justice.

52:31.748 --> 52:33.944
The first support
that we got was from

52:34.017 --> 52:37.146
the African-American community,
the Puerto Rican community.

52:37.220 --> 52:38.710
We did not have to go
into Harlem

52:38.788 --> 52:40.517
to get them
to take the grapes out.

52:40.590 --> 52:41.853
They did it on their own.

52:41.925 --> 52:43.256
The same thing in the Bronx

52:43.326 --> 52:45.226
with the Puerto Rican
brothers and sisters.

52:45.295 --> 52:47.127
They said,
"You want to get the grapes out?

52:47.197 --> 52:48.722
We'll get them out,"
and they did.

52:48.798 --> 52:51.010
But it was the farmworkers
themselves that went out there

52:51.034 --> 52:52.160
and told their stories,

52:52.235 --> 52:54.260
getting people involved
to volunteer

52:54.337 --> 52:56.135
to get those stores
to take the grapes out.

52:56.206 --> 53:00.234
I am not ashamed
because I am poor.

53:00.310 --> 53:03.336
I am proud
because I am a farmworker.

53:03.413 --> 53:04.690
All of the farmworkers grew.

53:04.714 --> 53:06.478
They learned to be
public speakers.

53:06.550 --> 53:08.484
Whereas they had been treated

53:08.552 --> 53:10.782
as dirt in the outside society,

53:10.854 --> 53:14.313
suddenly they were being given
a podium to tell their story

53:14.391 --> 53:18.624
and regain their own sense
of worth in that process.

53:18.695 --> 53:23.997
I didn't really
know Dolores before New York,

53:24.067 --> 53:25.660
but I think I was scared of her.

53:27.037 --> 53:31.406
I don't think that Dolores
thought I was worth the trouble

53:31.474 --> 53:33.841
until I got Huntington Hartford
to picket the A&P,

53:33.910 --> 53:36.106
which of course got press

53:36.179 --> 53:37.977
because the heir
to the A&P fortune

53:38.048 --> 53:40.949
was boycotting the A&P.

53:41.017 --> 53:42.951
After that, we became partners.

53:43.019 --> 53:47.388
My mother was raised
a Catholic and very traditional,

53:47.457 --> 53:49.516
and prior to going
to New York City,

53:49.593 --> 53:51.618
she really didn't speak
of feminism.

53:51.695 --> 53:53.424
I was in New York

53:53.496 --> 53:55.863
when the feminist movement
was being born,

53:55.932 --> 53:58.902
but my mind was focused
on getting all of those women

53:58.969 --> 54:01.597
at those conventions to support
the farmworkers.

54:01.671 --> 54:06.268
There was a time
when rarely could you discover

54:06.343 --> 54:09.870
women of color
who would identify as feminists

54:09.946 --> 54:15.680
because it was assumed to be
a question simply of gender

54:15.752 --> 54:18.449
and if it was a question
simply of gender,

54:18.521 --> 54:20.649
that gender was white.

54:20.724 --> 54:25.286
When social justice movements
arise in a patriarchal system,

54:25.362 --> 54:28.229
all kinds of false divisions
are made,

54:28.298 --> 54:30.494
and then there was
the additional problem

54:30.567 --> 54:34.629
in a lot of the Hispanic
community of Catholicism,

54:34.704 --> 54:37.696
which is especially oppressive
to women.

54:37.774 --> 54:40.052
I think that the feminist
movement is extremely important.

54:40.076 --> 54:45.708
I don't, of course,
agree with the idea of abortion

54:45.782 --> 54:50.083
because I do know from having 11
children that a fetus is live,

54:50.153 --> 54:51.814
you know?

54:51.888 --> 54:53.788
I think perhaps
in the beginning,

54:53.857 --> 54:56.622
she didn't quite see
that those of us

54:56.693 --> 54:59.253
who were supporting safe
and legal abortion

54:59.329 --> 55:05.701
are supporting the choice to
have a child just as fiercely,

55:05.769 --> 55:07.931
that we were advocating
the right of a woman

55:08.004 --> 55:10.871
to decide the fate
of her own physical self.

55:10.940 --> 55:14.035
That was difficult
for me at the beginning,

55:14.110 --> 55:18.411
but then it made me realize that
a woman really cannot decide

55:18.481 --> 55:20.449
what she wants to do
with her life

55:20.517 --> 55:22.417
unless she has the right
to decide

55:22.485 --> 55:25.284
how many children
she wants to have.

55:25.355 --> 55:28.188
It took us all a while

55:28.258 --> 55:29.783
to get over our divisions,

55:29.859 --> 55:33.659
but we came to realize that
if we had the same adversaries,

55:33.730 --> 55:38.429
we had a lot in common
and needed to organize together.

55:38.501 --> 55:42.028
I was out there fighting
for the Mexican-American movement,

55:42.105 --> 55:43.470
but I was not focused

55:43.540 --> 55:45.474
on the rights
of Mexican-American women.

55:45.542 --> 55:48.011
I think that was the big shift
that I had.

55:48.078 --> 55:50.740
I hope you don't mind
if I give a minute of that time

55:50.814 --> 55:54.182
first to Dolores Huerta
from the Farm Workers.

55:54.250 --> 55:55.911
Down with grapes!

55:55.985 --> 55:57.248
<i>IAbajo!</i>

55:57.320 --> 55:58.788
Down with Gallo wine!

55:58.855 --> 56:00.050
<i>IAbajo!</i>

56:00.123 --> 56:01.682
Down with violence!

56:01.758 --> 56:03.157
<i>IAbajo!</i>

56:03.226 --> 56:04.716
Down with racism!

56:04.794 --> 56:06.159
<i>IAbajo!</i>

56:06.229 --> 56:07.754
Down with sexism!

56:07.831 --> 56:09.060
<i>IAbajo!</i>

56:09.132 --> 56:14.468
<i>Si, se puede, si, se puede,
everybody.</i>

56:14.537 --> 56:18.974
I know that she set me on
fire in terms of racial injustice.

56:19.042 --> 56:21.534
I would not have been able
to see what's hidden

56:21.611 --> 56:25.172
in the fields of our country
without Dolores.

56:25.248 --> 56:26.738
We've picketed all of the firms

56:26.816 --> 56:29.148
that were carrying
scab grapes today,

56:29.219 --> 56:31.779
and we've gotten commitments
from several of the people

56:31.855 --> 56:34.347
out here that they won't handle
scab grapes anymore.

56:34.424 --> 56:38.486
There is no strike
in the vineyards.

56:38.561 --> 56:42.555
The Chavez group, representing
at best a tiny minority,

56:42.632 --> 56:46.296
are seeking to force,
by what amounts to blackmail,

56:46.369 --> 56:51.466
the growers to recognize their
group as the bargaining agent.

56:53.009 --> 56:56.912
I think that the
growers could not envision

56:56.980 --> 57:00.143
their serfs

57:00.216 --> 57:04.084
standing up for themselves
and demanding fair treatment.

57:04.154 --> 57:08.250
And they just couldn't
come to grips with that.

57:08.324 --> 57:11.760
You had the most
exploited workers in this country

57:11.828 --> 57:13.887
rising up and pushing back

57:13.963 --> 57:17.490
and pushing back
in a very effective way,

57:17.567 --> 57:19.262
building coalitions.

57:19.335 --> 57:23.272
Cesar, Dolores, los demés,
they looked like the people

57:23.339 --> 57:24.829
that they were representing.

57:24.908 --> 57:27.070
I think that scared
the hell out of them.

57:27.143 --> 57:28.804
If they should succeed
with this illegal

57:28.878 --> 57:30.471
and this immoral maneuver,

57:30.547 --> 57:32.914
they then move through
the agricultural community

57:32.982 --> 57:34.177
of California.

57:36.085 --> 57:38.076
The administration was buying
even more grapes

57:38.154 --> 57:41.818
to send, ironically,
to the soldiers in Vietnam

57:41.891 --> 57:43.859
by the thousands of pounds.

57:43.927 --> 57:47.090
I mean it was total
government interference.

57:47.163 --> 57:52.465
So this was very clearly
not only a battle

57:52.535 --> 57:54.663
against the growers.

57:54.737 --> 57:56.398
It was a battle
against the government

57:56.473 --> 57:57.716
and their support of the growers

57:57.740 --> 58:00.937
who had helped to put them
in office.

58:01.010 --> 58:03.445
It was political
from the beginning.

58:03.580 --> 58:07.778
I'm against the grape boycott
and I stand firmly against it.

58:11.054 --> 58:13.682
I think Dolores
and the leadership,

58:13.756 --> 58:16.350
they knew what they
were up against.

58:16.426 --> 58:17.552
What the union did

58:17.627 --> 58:19.220
is they made it
a national issue,

58:19.295 --> 58:23.129
and once the moral imperative
became part of the issue,

58:23.199 --> 58:29.161
then whatever power they have,
you've got to crack it.

58:31.975 --> 58:33.552
At the height of the boycott,

58:33.576 --> 58:36.409
there were around
17 million people

58:36.479 --> 58:38.106
who had stopped eating grapes,

58:38.181 --> 58:40.479
and it was
a pretty incredible feeling

58:40.550 --> 58:43.144
to know that people
were receptive to it.

58:43.219 --> 58:44.914
That's what the
grape boycott was.

58:44.988 --> 58:48.481
It was a mass coalition
of people that came together

58:48.558 --> 58:51.220
and helped the poorest people
in the land

58:51.294 --> 58:55.356
bring the most powerful people
in the state of California

58:55.431 --> 58:57.422
to the negotiations table.

58:57.500 --> 58:59.468
Why did you sign with the union?

58:59.536 --> 59:00.779
Why did you negotiate
the contract?

59:00.803 --> 59:02.567
Well, it was the effects
of the boycott.

59:04.874 --> 59:07.809
There it is, the
union stamp, the eagle,

59:07.877 --> 59:09.675
the symbol of the
United Farm Workers,

59:09.746 --> 59:11.942
and now the symbol of victory.

59:12.015 --> 59:16.976
After ten years of struggling,
these now are union vineyards.

59:17.053 --> 59:19.112
My mother had
negotiated an agreement

59:19.188 --> 59:22.214
with the Schenley Corporation
a few years before,

59:22.292 --> 59:25.557
but having reached an agreement
with an entire industry

59:25.628 --> 59:27.892
went beyond people's
initial expectations.

59:27.964 --> 59:31.457
The dream of a union
was now reality.

59:31.534 --> 59:35.767
For the first time, we
began to understand that we were,

59:35.838 --> 59:38.739
in fact, the architects
of our own destiny.

59:38.808 --> 59:40.970
The grape boycott, above all,

59:41.044 --> 59:42.739
shows strategy does
make a difference.

59:42.812 --> 59:46.214
You can have a big heart,
try your best, work 24/7.

59:46.282 --> 59:48.341
If you don't have the right
strategies and tactics,

59:48.418 --> 59:49.647
you're not going to succeed.

59:49.719 --> 59:51.551
Organizing,
it does make a difference.

59:51.621 --> 59:55.854
Under the new contracts,
the wages increase each year.

59:55.925 --> 59:58.257
There are paid vacations
and other fringe benefits.

59:58.328 --> 01:00:02.822
The most important is insurance
and a good medical plan.

01:00:02.899 --> 01:00:05.834
All of that was barely
dreamed of a few years ago

01:00:05.902 --> 01:00:08.564
by most of the pickers.

01:00:20.350 --> 01:00:22.250
LORI de LEON: After my
mother went to New York,

01:00:22.318 --> 01:00:26.346
I think it solidified her
beliefs in the power of women.

01:00:26.422 --> 01:00:27.821
I mean, she knew it,

01:00:27.890 --> 01:00:30.484
but it just took it
to a whole different level.

01:00:30.560 --> 01:00:33.586
And when she came back
to the union,

01:00:33.663 --> 01:00:35.722
she stood up more for herself

01:00:35.798 --> 01:00:39.757
with the executive board,
which were all men.

01:00:39.836 --> 01:00:43.295
She wasn't so much asking
for permission to do things,

01:00:43.373 --> 01:00:47.105
she just did what she felt
needed to be done.

01:00:47.176 --> 01:00:52.580
And I think Cesar felt he lost
a little bit of control of her.

01:00:52.649 --> 01:00:56.847
She realized
the knowledge and skillset

01:00:56.919 --> 01:01:00.355
that she brought
to this partnership

01:01:00.423 --> 01:01:01.982
so it became more challenging.

01:01:04.794 --> 01:01:07.525
The relationship
between Cesar and my mother

01:01:07.597 --> 01:01:08.792
was extremely complicated.

01:01:08.865 --> 01:01:10.731
They were probably
the best of friends

01:01:10.800 --> 01:01:12.878
and they had the most passionate
and heated arguments

01:01:12.902 --> 01:01:14.392
that I've ever heard.

01:01:14.470 --> 01:01:16.837
There's got to be
a time where the two of you

01:01:16.906 --> 01:01:18.237
don't agree on something.

01:01:18.307 --> 01:01:19.240
What do you do?

01:01:19.308 --> 01:01:21.072
Well, we would fight
with each other.

01:01:21.144 --> 01:01:24.114
We argue,
but it's always on the issue

01:01:24.180 --> 01:01:26.706
and then that's never been
a personality thing.

01:01:26.783 --> 01:01:28.581
LORI de LEON:
They were each other's peers.

01:01:28.651 --> 01:01:32.349
She felt she had every right
to speak up and say her piece

01:01:32.422 --> 01:01:34.390
and he didn't like that.

01:01:34.457 --> 01:01:36.802
He would fire her and she'd say,
"I quit," but she'd be there,

01:01:36.826 --> 01:01:38.555
the first one in the office
the next day,

01:01:38.628 --> 01:01:41.222
and it would be
business as usual.

01:01:41.297 --> 01:01:44.232
She and Cesar
were having a heated argument,

01:01:44.300 --> 01:01:48.294
and Dolores walks out of the
room and in Spanish she says:

01:01:54.811 --> 01:01:59.044
Growing up, we saw
so many people bowing down to him

01:01:59.115 --> 01:02:02.779
and it was really hard
to see that she was a person

01:02:02.852 --> 01:02:04.320
who was just real with him,

01:02:04.387 --> 01:02:06.355
you know, like nobody else
would be.

01:02:06.422 --> 01:02:09.790
My Tio Cesar was
surrounded by a lot of yes men

01:02:09.859 --> 01:02:11.793
and she was not the yes man.

01:02:11.861 --> 01:02:14.762
She was the chief negotiator.

01:02:14.831 --> 01:02:17.300
She was the cool head
and hard as nails,

01:02:17.366 --> 01:02:18.162
and people knew it,

01:02:18.234 --> 01:02:20.862
and yet there was a group of men

01:02:20.937 --> 01:02:23.167
that preferred to do things
without her.

01:02:23.239 --> 01:02:26.971
I saw a lot of resistance
to her leadership,

01:02:27.043 --> 01:02:29.034
putting obstacles or blocks,

01:02:29.112 --> 01:02:32.980
and it clearly only was because
she was a woman.

01:02:33.049 --> 01:02:35.984
I even said to Cesar
at one point in time, I said,

01:02:36.052 --> 01:02:39.613
"Look, we have a lot of machismo
here in the farmworkers movement

01:02:39.689 --> 01:02:42.659
and I am not going
to take it anymore."

01:02:42.725 --> 01:02:46.059
One year when she
came out in a national magazine,

01:02:46.129 --> 01:02:50.225
she criticized her own union
for being sexist.

01:02:50.299 --> 01:02:52.099
And I remember,
she called me up and she said,

01:02:52.135 --> 01:02:53.625
"Oh, shit's going
to hit the fan,"

01:02:53.703 --> 01:02:56.138
because, you know, as soon
as it gets out and Cesar...

01:02:56.205 --> 01:02:57.645
She said everybody was
pissed at her.

01:02:57.707 --> 01:03:01.701
I thought that was incredibly
brave of her to do that.

01:03:01.778 --> 01:03:06.011
Through her example, she
was able to get other women

01:03:06.082 --> 01:03:08.949
to assume leadership roles
within the union.

01:03:09.018 --> 01:03:11.851
Before Dolores, it was all men

01:03:11.921 --> 01:03:15.516
and that was the expectation
that it was men's work.

01:03:15.591 --> 01:03:17.958
The only reason
that we've been able

01:03:18.027 --> 01:03:19.620
to eliminate our enemies
one by one...

01:03:19.695 --> 01:03:23.598
Nixon, Reagan, the growers,
the labor contractors-

01:03:23.666 --> 01:03:27.432
the reason that we're going
to win is because of the marches

01:03:27.503 --> 01:03:30.097
and the strikes, the boycotts,
and the sacrifices of time

01:03:30.173 --> 01:03:33.234
and our families,
you know, going to jail.

01:03:33.309 --> 01:03:35.505
This is the reason
that we've been able to survive.

01:03:43.653 --> 01:03:45.451
We had contracts,

01:03:45.521 --> 01:03:46.818
not only in California.

01:03:46.889 --> 01:03:49.654
We had contracts in Arizona, New
Mexico, and even parts of Texas.

01:03:49.725 --> 01:03:54.458
LORI de LEON: Workers saw the benefits
of the contracts-the wage increase,

01:03:54.530 --> 01:03:57.227
the safety regulations where
they couldn't spray pesticides

01:03:57.300 --> 01:03:59.462
while the workers
were in the fields,

01:03:59.535 --> 01:04:01.560
but the contracts
were only three-year contracts.

01:04:01.637 --> 01:04:05.073
So in 1973, the growers signed
a sweetheart contract

01:04:05.141 --> 01:04:07.041
with the Teamsters Union.

01:04:07.109 --> 01:04:10.773
Well, are the Teamsters
Union easier for the farm growers

01:04:10.847 --> 01:04:12.007
to deal with than you people?

01:04:12.048 --> 01:04:13.675
Oh, much so, yes.

01:04:13.749 --> 01:04:15.994
Yes, because they don't make
any demands on the employers.

01:04:16.018 --> 01:04:17.729
See, the Teamsters Union
came into agriculture

01:04:17.753 --> 01:04:20.916
to protect the growers
from the United Farm Workers.

01:04:20.990 --> 01:04:23.482
So under the so-called
Teamster contracts,

01:04:23.559 --> 01:04:25.618
the farmworkers don't really get
any protections.

01:04:29.065 --> 01:04:31.193
LORI de LEON: So at that time,
workers went on strike.

01:04:31.267 --> 01:04:33.167
At issue is the future

01:04:33.236 --> 01:04:34.897
of the United Farm
Workers Union.

01:04:34.971 --> 01:04:36.097
The opposition force

01:04:36.172 --> 01:04:39.039
is the biggest and richest union
in the world.

01:04:39.108 --> 01:04:41.509
The Teamsters have poured
both money and muscle

01:04:41.577 --> 01:04:45.104
into the fight to represent
all California grape workers.

01:04:45.181 --> 01:04:47.843
You're a lousy bunch
of commie bums!

01:04:47.917 --> 01:04:49.078
He's not afraid.

01:04:49.151 --> 01:04:51.142
You stink! You smell!

01:04:51.220 --> 01:04:53.746
LORI de LEON: They had all
these injunctions against us.

01:04:53.823 --> 01:04:57.657
So, there was a decision made
to go ahead and violate them.

01:04:57.727 --> 01:05:02.096
Sheriff's deputies have
arrested the reported 1,700 farmworkers

01:05:02.164 --> 01:05:04.633
on picket lines
in four counties.

01:05:04.700 --> 01:05:07.465
The arrests have given
new impetus to the farmworkers

01:05:07.536 --> 01:05:10.005
in this battle
the Teamsters have called

01:05:10.072 --> 01:05:12.370
a fight to the finish.

01:05:12.441 --> 01:05:15.103
LORI de LEON: After that
came all the violence.

01:06:17.940 --> 01:06:22.104
My great-grandfather was
in the Civil War on the Union side.

01:06:22.178 --> 01:06:25.978
My father was in the military.

01:06:26.048 --> 01:06:27.743
My brother was in the military.

01:06:27.817 --> 01:06:29.546
And I remember when I first read

01:06:29.618 --> 01:06:32.053
the Constitution of the
United States in grammar school,

01:06:32.121 --> 01:06:36.615
I always felt so proud
of being an American.

01:06:36.692 --> 01:06:39.059
I thought, "God, we have
all these rights," you know.

01:06:39.128 --> 01:06:40.892
In a democracy,
you make your demands

01:06:40.963 --> 01:06:42.727
and then somebody
will listen to you.

01:06:42.798 --> 01:06:43.959
Justice will prevail.

01:06:44.033 --> 01:06:46.730
But I found out
that when you do this

01:06:46.802 --> 01:06:51.137
in an economic situation,
it doesn't quite work like that.

01:06:51.207 --> 01:06:53.539
Once we started making
those kind of demands,

01:06:53.609 --> 01:06:57.910
we had the same response
that the black movement has had.

01:06:57.980 --> 01:07:01.575
Our people were killed.

01:07:01.650 --> 01:07:07.020
The system doesn't really want
brown people or black people

01:07:07.089 --> 01:07:11.083
to have an organization
and to have any power.

01:07:11.160 --> 01:07:14.186
I found out that no matter
what I did,

01:07:14.263 --> 01:07:18.666
I could never be an American.

01:07:18.734 --> 01:07:19.758
Never.

01:07:32.114 --> 01:07:35.379
Big business and agribusiness,

01:07:35.451 --> 01:07:37.010
and racist police departments,

01:07:37.086 --> 01:07:39.077
or corrupt police departments,

01:07:39.155 --> 01:07:42.420
whoever it is
that's taking part in that,

01:07:42.491 --> 01:07:44.491
nobody's ever been convicted
for any of the murders

01:07:44.560 --> 01:07:46.927
of any of the martyrs
of the United Farm Workers.

01:07:46.996 --> 01:07:50.455
You know, think about that.

01:07:50.533 --> 01:07:55.903
That animosity is visceral, and
it's hate, and it's racial hate.

01:07:55.971 --> 01:08:01.375
You know, it's basically
the economics of racism.

01:08:01.444 --> 01:08:03.355
They were willing to sign
contracts with the Teamsters,

01:08:03.379 --> 01:08:06.178
pay a lot of money
as long as the workers

01:08:06.248 --> 01:08:07.545
can be kept oppressed.

01:08:07.616 --> 01:08:11.348
They will not accept workers
as their equals.

01:08:13.289 --> 01:08:14.499
You've been fighting so long.

01:08:14.523 --> 01:08:16.184
Do you ever get so tired
of fighting

01:08:16.258 --> 01:08:18.920
you think you can't do it
another day?

01:08:18.993 --> 01:08:22.897
Well, I haven't felt that way.

01:08:22.965 --> 01:08:24.228
You have to have commitment.

01:08:24.300 --> 01:08:25.768
It's got to be a total
commitment.

01:08:25.835 --> 01:08:28.202
It's not something that you can
just come in and leave.

01:08:28.270 --> 01:08:29.897
You've got to stay there
and keep working

01:08:29.971 --> 01:08:31.962
in order to make a difference.

01:08:32.041 --> 01:08:38.104
One has to understand
that Dolores does not waste time

01:08:38.180 --> 01:08:41.206
in negativity.

01:08:41.283 --> 01:08:43.341
Yes, what could we have done
better, et cetera,

01:08:43.419 --> 01:08:44.944
but it's forward.

01:08:45.020 --> 01:08:49.479
Do what has to be done and
move forward and move forward.

01:08:51.026 --> 01:08:52.737
California
legislature passed a farm bill

01:08:52.761 --> 01:08:55.321
it hopes will end violence
in the fields there.

01:08:55.397 --> 01:08:57.475
Under the new
Agricultural Labor Relations law,

01:08:57.500 --> 01:08:58.977
we'll be certified
as a bargaining representative

01:08:59.001 --> 01:09:01.197
and the employers have a duty
to bargain with us.

01:09:01.270 --> 01:09:02.714
Could you support Jimmy Carter?

01:09:02.738 --> 01:09:06.368
At this point, no,
unless he can really prove

01:09:06.442 --> 01:09:09.412
that he is willing to keep the
social contract with the people.

01:09:09.478 --> 01:09:12.607
The reason that we've
lost ground is political.

01:09:12.680 --> 01:09:15.149
It's because of the Agricultural
Labor Relations board.

01:09:15.216 --> 01:09:16.981
Because of the appointments
that were made,

01:09:17.051 --> 01:09:19.020
the growers refused to bargain.

01:09:19.087 --> 01:09:20.332
If we file charges,
they're dismissed.

01:09:20.356 --> 01:09:22.381
So there's no protections
out there for workers.

01:09:22.457 --> 01:09:25.291
Farmworkers still toil at
the bottom of the economic ladder,

01:09:25.361 --> 01:09:27.557
often exploited in ways
that are still shocking.

01:09:27.630 --> 01:09:29.550
Immigrants were
discouraged from voting.

01:09:29.598 --> 01:09:31.930
And so we have got to say
to them,

01:09:32.001 --> 01:09:33.310
"Look, it's okay
for you to vote."

01:09:33.335 --> 01:09:35.303
It's important and we want them
to participate

01:09:35.371 --> 01:09:36.462
in the political process.

01:09:36.538 --> 01:09:38.337
Work on the bill resumes today

01:09:38.407 --> 01:09:39.984
with debate centered on
the controversial amendment

01:09:40.009 --> 01:09:41.841
granting amnesty
to illegal aliens.

01:09:41.911 --> 01:09:44.312
Since we do have a
special legalization program

01:09:44.380 --> 01:09:45.745
for the farmworkers,

01:09:45.814 --> 01:09:47.459
they will not be afraid then
to make complaints

01:09:47.483 --> 01:09:49.027
if they know
that they won't get deported.

01:09:49.051 --> 01:09:51.062
It's going to make a tremendous
amount of difference.

01:09:51.086 --> 01:09:55.648
Some four million illegal
aliens are expected to seek amnesty.

01:09:57.026 --> 01:09:59.393
We are ready to give those
people permanent residency.

01:10:00.963 --> 01:10:03.163
But the growers don't
want them to be legalized

01:10:03.232 --> 01:10:04.757
because once they're legalized,

01:10:04.833 --> 01:10:06.995
they can protest
against pesticide poisoning.

01:10:07.069 --> 01:10:10.266
They can protest the low wages
that they're being given.

01:10:11.807 --> 01:10:13.536
George Bush spent the day
in California

01:10:13.609 --> 01:10:16.078
talking about the economy
and the need for compassion.

01:10:16.145 --> 01:10:17.943
Last night in San Francisco,

01:10:18.013 --> 01:10:21.244
police moved in to break up
a protest outside a fund raiser

01:10:21.317 --> 01:10:22.648
for the vice president.

01:10:22.718 --> 01:10:24.948
I must say,
you have a peculiar breed

01:10:25.020 --> 01:10:26.579
of demonstrators out there.

01:10:26.655 --> 01:10:29.750
They're giving me grief there
and his hair was flying around

01:10:29.825 --> 01:10:31.418
and, "No drilling! No drilling!"

01:10:31.493 --> 01:10:34.326
I finally said,
"I don't want to do anything

01:10:34.396 --> 01:10:35.807
that's going to hurt
the environment."

01:10:35.831 --> 01:10:38.232
"What about contras?
What about contras?"

01:10:38.300 --> 01:10:40.598
I'm glad to be inside.

01:10:44.673 --> 01:10:49.372
My friends...
Yes, I do mean friends...

01:10:49.445 --> 01:10:54.007
We know how to secure
a more just and prosperous life

01:10:54.083 --> 01:10:58.418
for man on earth,
with free markets, free speech,

01:10:58.487 --> 01:11:02.253
free elections,
and the exercise of free will

01:11:02.324 --> 01:11:05.089
unhampered by the state.

01:11:05.160 --> 01:11:10.496
America is never wholly herself
unless she is engaged

01:11:10.566 --> 01:11:14.662
in high moral principle,

01:11:14.737 --> 01:11:18.071
for democracy belongs to us all.

01:11:18.140 --> 01:11:22.543
No one is quite sure
how things got out of hand

01:11:22.611 --> 01:11:25.410
at the demonstration outside
the hotel where George Bush

01:11:25.481 --> 01:11:27.245
was speaking last night.

01:11:27.316 --> 01:11:31.150
This police footage
clearly shows.

01:11:31.220 --> 01:11:33.655
UFW leader Dolores Huerta

01:11:33.722 --> 01:11:38.023
trying to move as ordered
by police.

01:12:13.162 --> 01:12:18.726
A crowd control officer
bashed her body with a police baton

01:12:18.801 --> 01:12:21.771
and when we thought
that we lost her,

01:12:21.837 --> 01:12:25.535
it was really scary
and really unexpected.

01:12:25.607 --> 01:12:30.807
I was not ready to lose my mom
before turning 20 years old.

01:12:30.879 --> 01:12:33.871
Tonight, Dolores
Huerta is recovering

01:12:33.949 --> 01:12:36.646
from three broken ribs
and emergency surgery

01:12:36.719 --> 01:12:38.312
that removed her spleen.

01:12:38.387 --> 01:12:39.980
Huerta's son Emilio

01:12:40.055 --> 01:12:42.251
is grateful to the hospital
she is alive.

01:12:42.324 --> 01:12:44.349
Without their support,

01:12:44.426 --> 01:12:46.827
she would not be alive today.

01:12:52.067 --> 01:12:54.832
It was very hard
to see this powerful, strong,

01:12:54.903 --> 01:12:59.864
beautiful, like intimidating
woman just be reduced,

01:12:59.942 --> 01:13:03.674
you know, to just being
bedridden, you know.

01:13:06.415 --> 01:13:10.977
If you could use one
adjective to describe Dolores,

01:13:11.053 --> 01:13:12.680
it is dynamic.

01:13:12.755 --> 01:13:18.626
So the hardest thing that could
happen to her is to be immobile.

01:13:18.694 --> 01:13:24.656
She was lying in bed and looking
terrible, physically,

01:13:24.733 --> 01:13:27.464
and I just felt terrible
and said,

01:13:27.536 --> 01:13:29.527
"Dolores, what can I do
for you?"

01:13:29.605 --> 01:13:34.771
And she just said,
"Boycott Safeway."

01:13:36.178 --> 01:13:39.273
The only good thing
that I can think that came

01:13:39.348 --> 01:13:44.377
out of that experience was that
it was forced family time.

01:13:44.453 --> 01:13:47.081
And so we all got to have
as much of my mom

01:13:47.156 --> 01:13:48.317
as we wanted around.

01:13:48.390 --> 01:13:51.485
My kids were with me 24 hours.

01:13:51.560 --> 01:13:53.824
They took turns, 24 hours.

01:13:53.896 --> 01:13:55.921
I was sick
for many, many months.

01:13:55.998 --> 01:13:58.729
They never left me alone,
not even one day.

01:13:58.801 --> 01:14:01.827
And when you think about all the
times that I left them alone

01:14:01.904 --> 01:14:04.305
with different people
taking care of them,

01:14:04.373 --> 01:14:05.932
sometimes complete strangers,

01:14:06.008 --> 01:14:10.275
and yet they were so kind
to take care of me.

01:14:10.345 --> 01:14:12.624
It was interesting,
because all her children

01:14:12.648 --> 01:14:14.673
got together to support her,

01:14:14.750 --> 01:14:16.548
and that's when she realized

01:14:16.618 --> 01:14:18.643
that family
was really important to her.

01:14:20.422 --> 01:14:25.258
There was a reconciliation
on the part of the children too

01:14:25.327 --> 01:14:26.488
with their mother.

01:14:26.562 --> 01:14:29.293
That was sort of an awakening.

01:14:29.364 --> 01:14:32.629
We felt that we needed to be
less critical of my mother

01:14:32.701 --> 01:14:34.294
and her lifestyle,

01:14:34.369 --> 01:14:37.395
and we needed to support
my mother more

01:14:37.473 --> 01:14:41.103
in whatever role
that she decided to take on.

01:15:11.807 --> 01:15:14.003
LORI de LEON: After that
incident in San Francisco,

01:15:14.076 --> 01:15:18.172
you know, it took her a long
time to recover and come back.

01:15:18.247 --> 01:15:24.448
And her absence made Cesar
more aware of her importance.

01:15:24.520 --> 01:15:29.048
Her coming back
and being there 100%

01:15:29.124 --> 01:15:31.821
reestablished his commitment
to her.

01:15:31.894 --> 01:15:34.886
I remember when they
were working together,

01:15:34.963 --> 01:15:38.627
she came home and she said, "You
know what Cesar told me today?"

01:15:38.700 --> 01:15:42.159
"He thanked me for keeping him
honest all these years.

01:15:42.237 --> 01:15:43.671
Those were his words."

01:15:43.739 --> 01:15:45.867
She goes,
"I was taken aback by that."

01:15:45.941 --> 01:15:50.378
That was so unusual of
Cesar because within a few moments

01:15:50.445 --> 01:15:51.776
that we were together,

01:15:51.847 --> 01:15:53.941
we would usually be picking
a fight with each other.

01:15:54.016 --> 01:16:00.251
His whole behavior was so...
not like Cesar.

01:16:08.230 --> 01:16:11.530
As long as there's one
ounce of strength in our bodies,

01:16:11.600 --> 01:16:13.500
that ounce of strength
will be used

01:16:13.569 --> 01:16:14.934
to fight for this good cause.

01:16:15.003 --> 01:16:18.837
And in the end, we will win.

01:16:24.179 --> 01:16:27.240
Cesar Chavez was found
dead yesterday in Arizona,

01:16:27.316 --> 01:16:29.648
apparently of natural causes.

01:16:29.718 --> 01:16:32.415
An estimated 25,000 people
turned out Thursday

01:16:32.487 --> 01:16:34.455
in Delano, California,
for the funeral

01:16:34.523 --> 01:16:36.082
of labor leader Cesar Chavez,

01:16:36.158 --> 01:16:40.618
many of them farmworkers
Chavez helped to organize.

01:16:42.965 --> 01:16:46.993
I know she
misses my Tio Cesar a lot.

01:16:47.069 --> 01:16:48.833
He was a glue.

01:16:48.904 --> 01:16:52.738
He was like a certain
binding agent, you know?

01:16:55.110 --> 01:16:57.841
Like you miss the sun
on a cloudy day.

01:16:57.913 --> 01:16:59.278
You know what I'm saying?

01:17:02.851 --> 01:17:06.719
Who will fill his shoes or
what process will you go through?

01:17:06.788 --> 01:17:09.120
The executive board of the union
will be meeting

01:17:09.191 --> 01:17:11.489
and then they will decide
who the next president

01:17:11.560 --> 01:17:12.959
of the union will be.

01:17:13.028 --> 01:17:15.190
That is the process that we have
in our constitution.

01:17:15.263 --> 01:17:18.130
Do you feel you could
fill his shoes if you had to?

01:17:18.200 --> 01:17:22.034
Well, I think I worked
very many years with Cesar,

01:17:22.104 --> 01:17:24.937
but I think it's up
to the executive board

01:17:25.007 --> 01:17:27.738
to decide who they want,
you know.

01:17:29.711 --> 01:17:31.356
It certainly was an expectation

01:17:31.380 --> 01:17:34.281
on a number of people's part

01:17:34.349 --> 01:17:36.977
that when Cesar died,
Dolores would take it over

01:17:37.052 --> 01:17:40.352
since she had been in there
since the beginning.

01:17:40.422 --> 01:17:41.651
You could imagine,

01:17:41.723 --> 01:17:43.919
a farmworker's union
run by a woman?

01:17:43.992 --> 01:17:46.620
That would have been history.

01:17:46.695 --> 01:17:48.959
But she was not chosen.

01:17:49.031 --> 01:17:53.434
She called me to
tell me after Cesar passed

01:17:53.502 --> 01:17:57.439
that she was not going
to succeed Cesar as president

01:17:57.506 --> 01:18:01.204
and I, like, got so upset.

01:18:01.276 --> 01:18:04.871
And then she said to me
real calm, like super-calm,

01:18:04.946 --> 01:18:07.472
but I could tell
there was hurt in her voice,

01:18:07.549 --> 01:18:10.712
she said, "Barbara, it would be
one fight after another"

01:18:10.786 --> 01:18:12.254
if I fought for this."

01:18:12.320 --> 01:18:14.721
LORI de LEON:
The workers wanted her.

01:18:14.790 --> 01:18:16.280
The volunteers wanted her.

01:18:16.358 --> 01:18:18.622
The membership wanted her,

01:18:18.694 --> 01:18:19.923
but it was not about her,

01:18:19.995 --> 01:18:23.625
it was about
the union's survival.

01:18:23.699 --> 01:18:25.043
And so, she advocated
for someone else,

01:18:25.067 --> 01:18:27.195
Arturo Rodriguez
to become the president,

01:18:27.269 --> 01:18:31.866
who remains the president
of the union to this day.

01:18:34.409 --> 01:18:37.003
After that,
my mother started advocating

01:18:37.079 --> 01:18:41.949
to go back to the original way
of community organizing,

01:18:42.017 --> 01:18:47.046
but she was receiving a lot of
opposition from the leadership.

01:18:49.758 --> 01:18:51.783
I think there were indications
that her input

01:18:51.860 --> 01:18:55.319
was not as welcome
as one would have thought.

01:18:55.397 --> 01:19:00.801
LORI de LEON:
It was very hard to see that

01:19:00.869 --> 01:19:02.860
after all that my mother
had given,

01:19:02.938 --> 01:19:04.531
all the years of her life,

01:19:04.606 --> 01:19:06.973
putting the union
above all else,

01:19:07.042 --> 01:19:10.012
you know,
including all her 11 children.

01:19:12.214 --> 01:19:16.208
A lot of things
changed and I just felt that

01:19:16.284 --> 01:19:20.118
maybe it was really time
for me to leave and I left.

01:19:28.764 --> 01:19:31.028
I remember the convention

01:19:31.099 --> 01:19:33.761
where she actually gave
her resignation.

01:19:33.835 --> 01:19:38.272
It was a very emotional
experience

01:19:38.340 --> 01:19:41.002
and I think very difficult
for her.

01:19:42.244 --> 01:19:44.372
La compafiera, Dolores Huerta.

01:20:18.780 --> 01:20:22.307
LORI de LEON: I remember my sisters and
I and my brother being on the stage

01:20:22.384 --> 01:20:26.116
and surrounding my mother
for support.

01:21:02.624 --> 01:21:06.060
It was almost
like when Cesar died, you know?

01:21:06.127 --> 01:21:10.655
It was like a big part
of the farmworker thing dying.

01:21:10.732 --> 01:21:15.135
Everybody there was like...
I don't know, in shock,

01:21:15.203 --> 01:21:17.137
disbelief, you know.

01:21:17.205 --> 01:21:18.366
<i>G, Por qué, Dolores?</i>

01:21:18.440 --> 01:21:20.807
<i>No te vayas.</i>

01:21:20.876 --> 01:21:22.435
<i>No puedes.</i>

01:21:22.510 --> 01:21:23.978
<i>Z, Qué vamos a hacer'?</i>

01:21:24.045 --> 01:21:27.675
I tell you, there wasn't
a dry eye in the house.

01:21:55.710 --> 01:21:58.611
Dolores Huerta!

01:21:58.680 --> 01:22:00.671
Dolores Huerta!

01:22:00.749 --> 01:22:02.239
Dolores Huerta!

01:22:24.639 --> 01:22:27.074
I can't imagine
what she went through

01:22:27.142 --> 01:22:31.511
resigning from the union.

01:22:31.579 --> 01:22:36.676
There had to have been some
grieving, but knowing Dolores,

01:22:36.751 --> 01:22:40.688
there also had to have been some
si, se puede moments also,

01:22:40.755 --> 01:22:45.352
"I'm going to do something
significant despite this."

01:22:47.228 --> 01:22:50.664
Then she got
a Puffin/Nation award,

01:22:50.732 --> 01:22:53.463
which was $100,000 to do

01:22:53.535 --> 01:22:55.196
whatever she wanted
to do with it.

01:22:55.270 --> 01:22:58.205
There were no strings attached
at all.

01:22:58.273 --> 01:23:00.037
She could have kept that money

01:23:00.108 --> 01:23:02.440
to have a comfortable life
for herself,

01:23:02.510 --> 01:23:04.945
but Dolores has never been
interested

01:23:05.080 --> 01:23:07.344
in a comfortable life
for herself.

01:23:07.415 --> 01:23:11.977
After I'm feeling bad
about having to leave the union,

01:23:12.053 --> 01:23:13.885
I thought to myself,

